sh general election|1982 (Nov)]]\n| {{Composition bar|16|166|hex={{Labour Party (Ireland)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}}1\n| {{steady}}3rd\n| 158,115\n| 9.4%\n| style=\"background-color:PaleGreen\" |Coalition <small>(FG\u2013LP)</small>\n| [[Dick Spring]]\n|-\n![[1987 Irish general election|1987]]\n| {{Composition bar|12|166|hex={{Labour Party (Ireland)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{decrease}}4\n| {{decrease}}4th\n| 114,551\n| 6.4%\n| style=\"background-color:Pink\" |Opposition <small>(FF minority)</small>\n| Dick Spring\n|-\n![[1989 Irish general election|1989]]\n| {{Composition bar|15|166|hex={{Labour Party (Ireland)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}}3\n| {{increase}}3rd\n| 156,989\n| 9.5%\n| style=\"background-color:Pink\" |Opposition <small>(FF\u2013PD)</small>\n| Dick Spring\n|-\n![[1992 Irish general election|1992]]\n| {{Composition bar|33|166|hex={{Labour Party (Ireland)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}}18\n| {{steady}}3rd\n| 333,013\n| 19.3%\n| style=\"background-color:PaleGreen\" |Coalition <small>(FF\u2013LP)</small><br />Coalition <small>(FG\u2013LP\u2013DL from 1994)</small>\n| Dick Spring\n|-\n![[1997 Irish general election|1997]]\n| {{Composition bar|17|166|hex={{Labour Party (Ireland)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{decrease}}16\n| {{steady}}3rd\n| 186,044\n| 10.4%\n| style=\"background-color:Pink\" |Opposition <small>(FF)</small>\n| Dick Spring\n|-\n![[2002 Irish general election|2002]]\n| {{Composition bar|20|166|hex={{Labour Party (Ireland)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}}3\n| {{steady}}3rd\n| 200,130\n| 10.8%\n| style=\"background-color:Pink\" |Opposition <small>(FF)</small>\n| [[Ruairi Quinn]]\n|-\n![[2007 Irish general election|2007]]\n| {{Composition bar|20|166|hex={{Labour Party (Ireland)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{steady}}\n| {{steady}}3rd\n| 209,175\n| 10.1%\n| style=\"background-color:Pink\" |Opposition <small>(FF)</small>\n| [[Pat Rabbitte]]\n|-\n![[2011 Irish general election|2011]]\n| {{Composition bar|37|166|hex={{Labour Party (Ireland)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}}17\n| {{increase}}2nd\n| 431,796\n| 19.5%\n| style=\"background-color:PaleGreen\" |Coalition <small>(FG\u2013LP)</small>\n| [[Eamon Gilmore]]\n|-\n![[2016 Irish general election|2016]]\n| {{Composition bar|7|158|hex={{Labour Party (Ireland)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{decrease}}30\n| {{decrease}}4th\n| 140,898\n| 6.6%\n| style=\"background-color:Pink\" |Opposition <small>(FG\u2013Ind minority)</small>\n| [[Joan Burton]]\n|-\n![[2020 Irish general election|2020]]\n| {{Composition bar|6|160|hex={{Labour Party (Ireland)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{decrease}}1\n| {{decrease}}5th\n| 95,588\n| 4.4%\n| TBD\n| [[Brendan Howlin]]\n|}\n\n=== Northern Ireland ===\n==== Westminster ====\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Election\n! rowspan=2 | Leader\n! colspan=2 | Seats\n! rowspan=2 | Government\n|-\n! #\n! \u00b1\n|-\n! [[1950 United Kingdom general election|1950]]\n| [[William Norton]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{Infobox political party/seats|0|625|{{Labour Party (Ireland)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{steady}}\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n! [[1951 United Kingdom general election|1951]]\n| [[William Norton]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{Infobox political party/seats|1|625|{{Labour Party (Ireland)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}} 1\n| {{no2|Conservative}}\n|-\n! [[1955 United Kingdom general election|1955]]\n| [[William Norton]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{Infobox political party/seats|0|630|{{Labour Party (Ireland)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{decrease}} 1\n| {{n/a}}\n|}\n\n====Stormont====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!Election\n!Body\n!Seats\n!Outcome\n|-\n| align=center|[[1953 Northern Ireland general election|1953]]\n| align=center|{{sort|09|[[List of MPs elected in the Northern Ireland general election, 1953|8th Parliament]]}}\n| align=left  |{{Composition bar|1|52|hex={{Labour Party (Ireland)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{no2|UUP Majority}}\n|-\n| align=center|[[1958 Northern Ireland general election|1958]]\n| align=center|{{sort|09|[[List of MPs elected in the Northern Ireland general election, 1958|9th Parliament]]}}\n| align=left  |{{Composition bar|0|52|hex={{Labour Party (Ireland)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{no2|UUP Majority}}\n|-\n| align=center|[[1962 Northern Ireland general election|1962]]\n| align=center|{{sort|09|[[List of MPs elected in the Northern Ireland general election, 1962|10th Parliament]]}}\n| align=left  |{{Composition bar|1|52|hex={{Labour Party (Ireland)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{no2|UUP Majority}}\n|}\n\n==Structure==\nThe Labour Party is a membership organisation consisting of Labour ([[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann|D\u00e1il]]) constituency councils, affiliated [[trade union]]s and [[Socialist society (Labour Party)|socialist societies]]. Members who are elected to parliamentary positions (D\u00e1il, Seanad, European Parliament) form the Parliamentary Labour Party (PLP). The party's decision-making bodies on a national level formally include the Executive Board (formerly known as the National Executive Committee), Labour Party Conference and Central Council. The Executive Board has responsibility for organisation and finance, with the Central Council being responsible for policy formation \u2013 although in practice the Parliamentary leadership has the final say on policy. The Labour Party Conference debates motions put forward by branches, constituency councils, party members sections and affiliates. Motions set principles of policy and organisation but are not generally detailed policy statements.\n\nFor many years Labour held to a policy of not allowing residents of Northern Ireland to apply for membership, instead supporting the [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]] (SDLP). The National Conference approved the establishment of a Northern Ireland Members Forum but it has not agreed to contest elections there.\n\nAs a party with a constitutional commitment to [[democratic socialism]]<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.labour.ie/party/constitution.html |title=Party Constitution |publisher=Labour.ie |date=20 May 2009|accessdate=1 January 2011}}</ref> founded by trade unions to represent the interests of [[working class]] people, Labour's link with unions has always been a defining characteristic of the party. Over time this link has come under increasing strain, with most craft based unions based in the public sector and [[Irish Congress of Trades Unions]] having disaffiliated since the 1950s. The remaining affiliated unions are primarily private sector [[general union]]s. Currently affiliated unions still send delegates to the National Conference in proportion to the size of their membership. Recent{{when|date=July 2017}} constitutional changes mean that in future, affiliated unions will send delegations based on the number of party members in their organisation.\n\n===Sections===\nWithin the Labour Party there are different sections:\n*[[Labour Youth]]\n*[[Labour Women]]\n*Labour Trade Unionists\n*Labour [[Councillor]]s\n*Labour Equality (this section also includes groups such as Labour LGBT)\n*Labour Disability\n\n==Affiliates==\nThe Irish Labour Party constitution makes provision for both Trade Unions and Socialist Societies to affiliate to the party. There are currently seven Trade Unions affiliated to the Party:\n\n*Munster & District Graphical Society\n*[[F\u00f3rsa]] (Municipal Employees Division)\n*[[National Union of Rail, Maritime and Transport Workers]] (RMT)\n*[[GMB (trade union)|General, Municipal and Boilermakers' Union]] (GMB)\n*Services, Industrial, Professional and Technical Union ([[SIPTU]])\n*[[Bakers, Food and Allied Workers Union]] (BFWAU)\n*[[Transport Salaried Staffs Association]] (TSSA)\n\nSocialist Societies Affiliated to the Party:\n*Labour Party Lawyers Group\n*Association of Labour Teachers\n*Labour Social Services Group\n\n==Leadership==\n\n===Party leader===\n{{main|Leader of the Labour Party (Ireland)}}\nThe following are the terms of office as party leader and as T\u00e1naiste:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Portrait\n! Period\n! C