n|-\n|[[49th Annual Grammy Awards|2007]]\n|For Once In My Life\n|[[Tony Bennett]], [[Stevie Wonder]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental and Vocals|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[50th Annual Grammy Awards|2008]]\n|Cry Me A River\n|[[Ella Fitzgerald]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental and Vocals|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[54th Annual Grammy Awards|2012]]\n|Who Can I Turn To (When Nobody Needs Me)\n|[[Tony Bennett]], [[Queen Latifah]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental and Vocals|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[60th Annual Grammy Awards|2018]]\n|Every Time We Say Goodbye\n|[[Clint Holmes]], [[Jane Monheit]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental and Vocals|Best Arrangement, Instruments and Vocals]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|}\n<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XREEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA3&lpg=PA3&dq=jorge+calandrelli+++billboard&source=bl&ots=yYHdvg8PPO&sig=ACfU3U2IwIFNoxr0K0oGyiBrFZe7dttVuw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwil2_Ksz8voAhX-JTQIHad_A44Q6AEwBnoECAsQLg#v=onepage&q=calandrelli&f=false|title=Billboard|date=2004-02-07|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0129326|name=Jorge Calandrelli}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.jorgecalandrelli.com/}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Calandrelli, Jorge}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Argentine music arrangers]]\n[[Category:Argentine composers]]\n[[Category:Argentine musicians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin Grammy Award for Producer of the Year]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Latin music composers]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-composer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Jorge Calandrelli at DMI Grammy Party, 2014.jpg|thumb|Jorge Calandrelli in 2014]]\n'''Jorge Calandrelli''' is an Argentinian-born composer, arranger and conductor known for his work with [[Arturo Sandoval]], [[Yo-Yo Ma]], [[Elton John]], [[Lady Gaga]] and [[John Legend]]. He has won 4 [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]] and has received 27 nominations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afm47.org/press/michael-giacchino-jorge-calandrelli-to-be-honored-at-golden-score-awards/|title=Michael Giacchino, Jorge Calandrelli to be Honored at Golden Score Awards|last=admin|date=2014-09-16|website=47 Blog {{!}} AFM Local 47|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> He also holds 2 [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] nominations. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RsAnJ7Zx_qgC&pg=RA5-PA28&lpg=RA5-PA28&dq=jorge+calandrelli+++billboard&source=bl&ots=_92ogFrTue&sig=ACfU3U1UNuIxs5KwZFRORL8rSMucqERYVw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwil2_Ksz8voAhX-JTQIHad_A44Q6AEwBXoECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q=calandrelli&f=false|title=Billboard|date=2012-01-07|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/jorge-calandrelli|title=Jorge Calandrelli|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> He won the [[Latin Grammy Award for Producer of the Year]] and [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Album|Best Instrumental Album]] for his work on ''[[A Time for Love (Arturo Sandoval album)|A Time for Love]]'' by [[Arturo Sandoval]] in [[11th Annual Latin Grammy Awards|2010]].<ref name=LatinGrammy2010>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2010/09/latin-grammy-nominees-announced-alejandro-sanz-and-camila-among-top-contenders.html|title=Latin Grammy nominees announced: Alejandro Sanz and Camila among top contenders |work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Tribune Company|accessdate=January 25, 2011|date=September 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/es/nominees/search|title=20a Entrega Anual del Latin GRAMMY|website=Latin GRAMMYs|language=es|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and career ==\nWhile Calandrelli's mother was a skilled pianist, both his father and grandfather were medical doctors and expected him to follow their path. At age 4, Calandrelli started playing the piano by ear and started taking lessons at age 8.\n\nIn his late teens, with both of his parents' support, Calandrelli traveled to Europe to pursue a career in music. He arrived in [[Los Angeles]] in 1968 and collaborated with composer and arranger [[Clare Fischer]]. Inspired by him, Calandrelli decided to go back to Argentina and continue honing his skills.\n\nHe would later return to the United States with recommendation letters from the record labels we had worked with in Argentina. Soon, he recorded Russian-American conductor [[Andre Kostelanetz]] and a 65-piece orchestra at [[CBS]]' studio in [[New York City|New York]].\n\nCalandrelli soon started arranging for different artists, achieving a wider recognition in [[23rd Annual Grammy Awards|1981]] with first [[Grammy Award]] nomination for [[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental or A Cappella|Best Instrumental Arrangement]] for his work on \"Forget the Woman\" by [[Eddie Daniels]]. In 1987, he was nominated three times at the [[29th Annual Grammy Awards|29th Grammy Awards]]: in the [[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental or A Cappella|Best Arrangement on an Instrumental]] category for \"Solfeggietto/Metamorphosis\" by Eddie Daniels and \"The First Letter\" from [[The Color Purple (film)|The Color Purple]] soundtrack and in the [[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental and Vocals|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocals]] category for [[Tony Bennett|Tony Bennett's]] version of Daniels' \"Forget The Woman \".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RsAnJ7Zx_qgC&pg=RA5-PA28&lpg=RA5-PA28&dq=jorge+calandrelli+++billboard&source=bl&ots=_92ogFrTue&sig=ACfU3U1UNuIxs5KwZFRORL8rSMucqERYVw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwil2_Ksz8voAhX-JTQIHad_A44Q6AEwBXoECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q=calandrelli&f=false|title=Billboard|date=2012-01-07|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.awardsandshows.com/features/grammy-awards-1987-235.html|title=Grammy Award Nominees 1987 - Grammy Award Winners 1987|website=www.awardsandshows.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nCalandrelli's work with Bennett includes twelve recorded albums, six Grammy Nominations and two Grammy Awards won.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jorge-calandrelli-mn0000987684/credits|title=Jorge Calandrelli {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Bennett's 2011 album \"[[Duets II (Tony Bennett album)|Duets II]]\", arranged and conducted by Calandrelli debuted at No. 1 on the [[Billboard 200]], Jazz Albums and Traditional Jazz Albums charts. This same No. 1 debut was achieved by Bennett's 2014 collaborative album with [[Lady Gaga]] \"[[Cheek to Cheek (album)|Cheek To Cheek]]\", also arranged and orchestrated by Calandrelli.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rivergrandrapids.com/must-see-tv-with-tony-bennet-lady-gaga-cheek-to-cheek-live/|title=Must See TV With Tony Bennet & Lady Gaga: Cheek To Cheek LIVE!|last=Andy Rent|website=100.5 The River|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nCalandrelli produced, played the piano, composed, arranged and conducted on [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo|Pl\u00e1cido Domingo's]] 2008 album \"Amore Infinito\", based on lyrics by [[Pope John Paul II]]. The album contains duets by [[Josh Groban]], [[Katherine Jenkins]], [[Andrea Bocelli]], [[Vanessa Williams]] and Pl\u00e1cido Domingo Jr.\n\n== Awards and accolades ==\n\n=== Golden Score Awards ===\nThe [[American Society of Music Arrangers and Composers|American Society of Music Arrangers and Composers (ASMAC)]] honored Calandrelli with the 2014 Golden Score Award for Arranging.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://parabuenosaires.com/la-legislatura-portena-distingue-al-maestro-jorge-calandrelli/|title=La Legislatura porte\u00f1a distingue al maestro Jorge Calandrelli|last=Aires|first=Parabuenosaires com {{!}} Noticias de Buenos|language=es|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.clarin.com/espectaculos/musica/jorge-calandrelli-pague-derecho-piso-unidos_0_Hkzn6QqZl.html|title=Jorge Calandrelli: \"Nunca pagu\u00e9 derecho de piso en los Estados Unidos\"|last=Clar\u00edn.com|website=www.clarin.com|language=es|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \n\n=== [[Academy Awards]] ===\nCalandrelli has been nominated twice at the Academy Awards for his work on [[The Color Purple (film)|The Color Purple]] and  [[Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== [[Latin Grammy Award|Latin Grammy Awards]] ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Artist\n!Category\n!Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[11th Annual Latin Grammy Awards|2010]]\n|[[A Time for Love (Arturo Sandoval album)|A Time for Love]]\n|[[Arturo Sandoval]]\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Album|Best Instrumental Album]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n| -\n| -\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Producer of the Year|Producer of the Year]]\n|{{Won}}\n|}\n<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]] ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Artist\n!Category\n!Result\n|-\n|[[23rd Annual Grammy Awards|1981]]\n|Forget The Woman\n|[[Eddie Daniels]]\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[29th Annual Grammy Awards|1987]]\n|Solfeggietto/Metamorphosis\n|[[Eddie Daniels]]\n|Best Arrangement on an Instrumental\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|The First Letter\n|[[Quincy Jones]]\n|Best Arrangement on an Instrumental\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|Forget The Woman\n|[[Tony Bennett]]\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocals\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[30th Annual Grammy Awards|1988]]\n|Any Time, Any Season\n|[[Sam Most]]\n|Best Arrangement on an Instrumental\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[33rd Annual Grammy Awards|1991]]\n|Body And Soul\n|[[Tony Bennett]]\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocals\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[38th Annual Grammy Awards|1996]]\n|Atras Da Porta\n|Ettore Stratta\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|Manha De Carnaval\n|Ettore Stratta\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[39th Annual Grammy Awards|1997]]\n|The Fifth Season\n|[[Eddie Daniels]]\n|Best Instrumental Composition\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|Summer\n|[[Eddie Daniels]]\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[41st Annual Grammy Awards|1999]]\n|Soul Of The Tango - The Music Of Astor Piazzolla\n|[[Yo-Yo Ma]]\n|Best Classical Crossover Album\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Tango Remembrances\n|[[Yo-Yo Ma]]\n|Best Instrumental Composition\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[42nd Annual Grammy Awards|2000]]\n|Chelsea Bridge\n|[[Wynton Marsalis]], [[Tony Bennett]]\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|Day Dream\n|[[Tony Bennett]]\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[43rd Annual Grammy Awards|2001]]\n|The Summer Knows/Estate\n|Ettore Stratta\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|Dream\n|Ettore Stratta\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying a Vocalist(s)\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[44th Annual Grammy Awards|2002]]\n|A Love Before Time\n|[[Coco Lee]]\n|Best Song Written for a Motion Picture or other Visual Media\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[45th Annual Grammy Awards|2003]]\n|Esta Tarde Vi Llover\n|[[Jos\u00e9 Cura]]\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[46th Annual Grammy Awards|2004]]\n|Obrigado Brazil\n|[[Yo-Yo Ma]]\n|Best Classical Crossover Album\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[Chega de Saudade|Chega De Saudade]]\n|[[Yo-Yo Ma]]\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|Oblivion\n|[[Regina Carter]]\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[47th Annual Grammy Awards|2005]]\n|Libertango\n|[[Yo-Yo Ma]]\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[48th Annual Grammy Awards|2006]]\n|Time To Smile\n|[[Tony Bennett]]\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[49th Annual Grammy Awards|2007]]\n|For Once In My Life\n|[[Tony Bennett]], [[Stevie Wonder]]\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[50th Annual Grammy Awards|2008]]\n|Cry Me A River\n|[[Ella Fitzgerald]]\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[54th Annual Grammy Awards|2012]]\n|Who Can I Turn To (When Nobody Needs Me)\n|[[Tony Bennett]], [[Queen Latifah]]\n|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[60th Annual Grammy Awards|2018]]\n|Every Time We Say Goodbye\n|[[Clint Holmes]], [[Jane Monheit]]\n|Best Arrangement, Instruments and Vocals\n|{{Nom}}\n|}\n<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XREEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA3&lpg=PA3&dq=jorge+calandrelli+++billboard&source=bl&ots=yYHdvg8PPO&sig=ACfU3U2IwIFNoxr0K0oGyiBrFZe7dttVuw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwil2_Ksz8voAhX-JTQIHad_A44Q6AEwBnoECAsQLg#v=onepage&q=calandrelli&f=false|title=Billboard|date=2004-02-07|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0129326|name=Jorge Calandrelli}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.jorgecalandrelli.com/}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Calandrelli, Jorge}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Argentine music arrangers]]\n[[Category:Argentine composers]]\n[[Category:Argentine musicians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin Grammy Award for Producer of the Year]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Latin music composers]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-composer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "TanookiKoopa", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added links, changed wording.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jorge_Calandrelli"}
{"title_page": "Missa brevis Sancti Joannis de Deo", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                  = ''Missa brevis Sancti Joannis de Deo''\n| type                  = [[List of masses by Joseph Haydn|Mass by Joseph Haydn]]\n| image                 = Haydnportrait.jpg\n| image_upright         = \n| caption               = The composer c. 1770, Portrait by {{nowrap|[[Ludwig Guttenbrunn]]}}\n| other_name            = ''Little Organ Mass''\n| key                   = [[B-flat major]]\n| catalogue             = [[Hoboken number|Hob.]] XXII:7\n| composed              = 1774\n| movements             = 6\n| vocal                 = {{plainlist|\n* [[SATB|{{abbr|SATB|soprano, alto, tenor and bass}}]] choir\n* soprano solo\n}}\n| instrumental          = {{hlist | 2 violins | organ | bass }}\n}}\nThe '''''{{lang|la|Missa brevis Sancti Joannis de Deo}}''''', [[Hoboken number|Hob.]] XXII:7, Novello 8, is a [[Mass (music)|mass]] in [[B-flat major]] by [[Joseph Haydn]].<ref>p. 265 (1974) Hugues</ref> The {{lang|la|[[missa brevis]]}} (short mass) was written around 1774 for the order of the {{lang|de|Barmherzige Br\u00fcder}} ([[Brothers Hospitallers of St. John of God|Brothers Hospitallers]]) in [[Eisenstadt]], whose [[patron saint]] was [[John of God]]. Scored modestly for soprano, four-part mixed choir, two violins, organ and bass, it is known as the '''Kleine Orgelmesse''' ('''Little Organ Mass''') due to an extended organ solo in the Benedictus movement.\n\n== History ==\nHaydn composed four or five short masses, depending on the ''Missa brevis Rorate coeli desuper'' being composed by him or not. The ''Missa brevis Sancti Joannis de Deo'' is his last {{lang|la|[[missa brevis]]}}. All these short masses share a modest orchestra.<ref name=\"MacIntyre\" />\n\nThe mass was written for the order of the {{lang|de|Barmherzige Br\u00fcder}}, also called Brothers of Mercy, in [[Eisenstadt]], [[Hungarian Kingdom]] (now Austria), whose founder and [[patron saint]] was St. [[John of God]].<ref name=\"Hyperion\">{{cite web| url = http://www.hyperion-records.co.uk/dw.asp?dc=W2581_66508 | title = Missa Brevis Sancti Joannis de Deo 'Small Organ Mass', Hob XXII:7 | publisher = [[Hyperion Records|Hyperion]] | accessdate = 22 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"p. blank 1989 McCaldin\">p. [blank] (1989) McCaldin</ref><ref name=\"p. blank 1989 McCaldin\"/> Haydn lived in Eisenstadt, working for the court of [[Nikolaus II, Prince Esterh\u00e1zy]]. The composition was written in 1774.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Alwes|first=Chester|title=A History of Western Choral Music: Volume 1|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=336}}</ref> Because of an extensive [[Organ (music)|Organ]] solo in the Benedictus, it is known as the Kleine Orgelmesse (Little Organ Mass),<ref name=\"Hyperion\" /> referring to the {{Interlanguage link multi|Missa in honorem Beatissimae Virginis Mariae|de|3=Gro\u00dfe Orgelsolomesse|lt=Gro\u00dfe Orgelsolomesse}} (Great Organ Mass), a colloquial name for the ''Missa in honorem Beatissimae Virginis Mariae'', Haydn's fourth mass in [[E-flat major]]. An organ solo in the Benedictus was common practice at the time.<ref name=\"MacIntyre\" />\n\nHaydn played the organ in the first performance,<ref name=\"Hsu\">{{cite web|url=http://atlantabaroque.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/2007-05-13-program.pdf|title=Handel and Haydn|last=Hsu|first=John|date=13 May 2007|publisher=atlantabaroque.org|accessdate=22 August 2015}}</ref> in the hospital chapel of the Brethren in Eisenstadt. \"Kleine\" (little) may refer to the composition as well as to the organ, because the instrument  there was a positive with six stops without pedal.<ref name=\"MacIntyre\" />\n\n== Scoring and structure ==\nThe setting of the [[Latin]] mass is structured in six movements. It was originally scored for a solo soprano, a four-part choir ([[SATB]]), the so-called ''{{lang|de|Wiener Kirchentrio}}'' (Vienna church trio) of two violins and bass, with an organ which has a solo function in the Benedictus.<ref name=\"Hyperion\" /><ref name=\"Morrison\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/composition/mc0002361608|title=Franz Joseph Haydn / Missa brevis St. Joannis de Deo, for soloists, chorus, organ & orchestra in B flat major (\"Little Organ Mass\"), H. 22/7|last=Morrison|first=Chris|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=22 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the following table of the movements, the voices, markings, [[Key (music)|keys]] and [[time signature]]s are taken from the choral score.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | No.\n! scope=\"col\" | Part\n! scope=\"col\" | Incipit\n! scope=\"col\" | Vocal\n! scope=\"col\" | Marking\n! scope=\"col\" | Key\n! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n| 1 || style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{lang|grc|[[#Kyrie|Kyrie]]}} || {{lang|grc|Kyrie}} || SATB || {{lang|it|Adagio}} || B-flat major || {{music|common-time}}\n|-\n| 2 || style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{lang|la|[[#Gloria|Gloria]]}} || {{lang|la|Gloria}} || SATB || {{lang|it|Allegro molto}} || B-flat major || 3/4\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 3 || rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{lang|la|[[#Credo|Credo]]}} || {{lang|la|Credo}} || SATB  || {{lang|it|Allegro}} || rowspan=\"3\" | B-flat major || {{music|common-time}}\n|-\n| {{lang|la|Et incarnatus est}} || SATB || {{lang|it|Adagio}} || rowspan=\"2\" | 3/4\n|-\n| {{lang|la|Et resurrexit}} || SATB || {{lang|it|Allegro}}\n|-\n| 4 || style=\"text-align: center;\"| {{lang|la|[[#Sanctus|Sanctus]]}} || {{lang|la|Sanctus}} || SATB || {{lang|it|Allegro}} || B-flat major || 6/8\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 5 || rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{lang|la|[[#Benedictus|Benedictus]]}} || {{lang|la|Benedictus}} || Soprano || {{lang|it|Moderato}} || E-flat major || {{music|common-time}}\n|-\n| {{lang|la|Osanna}} || SATB || {{lang|it|Allegro}} || B-flat major || 6/8\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 6 || style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{lang|la|[[#Agnus Dei|Agnus Dei]]}} || {{lang|la|Agnus Dei}} || SATB || {{lang|it|Adagio}} || B-flat major || 3/4\n|-\n|}\n\n== Music ==\nThe movements Gloria and Credo are kept extremely short by the technique of {{lang|de|{{Interlanguage link multi|Polytextur|de}}}} (multiple texts): \"several clauses of the text [are set] simultaneously in different voices.\"<ref name=\"Hyperion\" /><ref>p. 125 (1974) Hugues</ref> The texts from the order of mass are repeated in every mass and thus well known; The setting of different passages assigned to the different parts, heard simultaneously, does justice to the liturgy but keeps the music short. The Benedictus is the only movement which is not in B-flat major, and set for a solo voice.\n\n=== Kyrie ===\nThe Kyrie shows, according to the musicologist John Hsu \"brilliant instrumental idioms and choral declamation.<ref name=\"Hsu\" />\n<!--\n=== Gloria === -->\n\n=== Credo ===\nThe Credo is structured in three parts, the center being formed by an Adagio for the birth, suffering and death of Jesus, delivered by the choir mostly in [[homophony]], accompanied by broken chords in the violins and repetition in the bass. The third section recapitulates music from the Gloria.<ref name=\"Hsu\" />\n\n=== Sanctus ===\nSanctus is called by the voices in a fast sequence of entries, some as bell-like long notes, other in flowing triplets. For the Osanna, the voices enter from the lowest to the highest, only one measure apart. The instruments play [[colla parte]] with the voices, violins with soprano and alto, cello and [[violone]] with the bass.<ref name=\"Hsu\" />\n\n=== Benedictus ===\nThe Benedictus, the longest movement, is a dialogue of soprano soloist and organ, described as \"expressive, elegant, and ornate melodic lines\". It is followed by a repeat of the Osanna.<ref name=\"Hsu\" />\n\n=== Agnus Dei ===\nHaydn marked the Agnus Dei carefully for dramatic contrast in dynamics, setting \"Agnus Dei\" (Lamb of God) as a [[fortissimo]] homophonic call versus a [[Dynamics (music)|pianissimo]] prayer \"Dona nobis pacem\" (Give us peace).<ref name=\"Hsu\" /> The end is marked \"[[perdendosi]], senza organo\" (dying away, without organ), with a [[pizzicato]] bass.<ref name=\"MacIntyre\" />\n\nA reviewer of the Oxford edition summarized: \"The work is accessible to most choirs. The music is not excessively difficult, but the solid musical structure and the many passages requiring expressive singing make\nthe work a rewarding pleasure for any size choir.<ref name=\"MacIntyre\" /> [[H. C. Robbins Landon]], an editor of the composition, ascribed to the work a \"quiet spirit of devotion, even of mysticism, that is most appealing\".<ref name=\"Hyperion\" />\n\n== Versions ==\n\nWhile the mass was originally scored for choir, strings and organ, later versions include with [[trumpet]]s and [[timpani]], and [[clarinet]]s.<ref name=\"Hyperion\" />\n\nThe mass was also used in Salzburg where the textual compression was deemed \"unacceptable\", therefore the composer's brother [[Michael Haydn]] expanded the Gloria, from 31 measures to 118.<ref name=\"p. blank 1989 McCaldin\"/> Very few performances however, use this expansion. However, the [[Oxford University Press|Oxford edition]] presents Michael Haydn's prolongation in the main body of the text and Joseph's short original as an appendix.<ref name=\"MacIntyre\">{{cite web | last = MacIntyre | first = Bruce C. | jstor = 942089 | title = Joseph Haydn. Missa brevis SanctiJoannis de Deo (Hob. XXII:7) \"Little Organ Mass\" with Michael Haydn's prolongation of the Gloria. Edited by Denis McCaldin. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1989. | publisher = Music Library Association }}</ref><ref name=\"p. blank 1989 McCaldin\"/><ref>p. 458 (1989) Aston</ref> [[Johann Georg Albrechtsberger]] wrote an alternate Benedictus.<ref name=\"Hyperion\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Aston (1989) Peter. \"Review\" August ''Music & Letters'' No. 3, Vol. 70\n* Hugues (1974) Rosemary. London. ''Haydn''. J. M. Dent & Sons Ltd\n* McCaldin (1989) Denis. Introduction. Oxford. Franz Joseph Haydn: Missa brevis Sancti Joannis de Deo, Hob. XXII:7, Little Organ Mass, with prolongation by Michael Haydn. Oxford University Press\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{IMSLP2|work=Mass in B-flat major, Hob.XXII:7 (Haydn, Joseph)|cname=Mass in B-flat major, Hob.XXII:7}}\n* {{ChoralWiki|Kleine_Orgelmesse_(Mass_no._7_in_Bb_Major)_(Franz_Joseph_Haydn)|Missa brevis Sancti Joannis de Deo}}\n* Jones, Jill Ann: [http://scholarworks.sjsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1840&context=etd_theses A Historical Study of Joseph Haydn's Missa brevis Sancti Joannis de Deo Hob XXII:7] [[San Jose State University]] 1994\n\n{{Haydn masses}}\n\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Missa Brevis Sancti Joannis De Deo}}\n[[Category:Masses by Joseph Haydn]]\n[[Category:Music for orchestra and organ]]\n[[Category:1775 compositions]]\n[[Category:Compositions in B-flat major]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                  = ''Missa brevis Sancti Joannis de Deo''\n| type                  = [[List of masses by Joseph Haydn|Mass by Joseph Haydn]]\n| image                 = Haydnportrait.jpg\n| image_upright         = \n| caption               = The composer c. 1770, Portrait by {{nowrap|[[Ludwig Guttenbrunn]]}}\n| other_name            = ''Little Organ Mass''\n| key                   = [[B-flat major]]\n| catalogue             = [[Hoboken number|Hob.]] XXII:7\n| composed              = 1774\n| movements             = 6\n| vocal                 = {{plainlist|\n* [[SATB|{{abbr|SATB|soprano, alto, tenor and bass}}]] choir\n* soprano solo\n}}\n| instrumental          = {{hlist | 2 violins | organ | bass }}\n}}\nThe '''''{{lang|la|Missa brevis Sancti Joannis de Deo}}''''', [[Hoboken number|Hob.]] XXII:7, Novello 8, is a [[Mass (music)|mass]] in [[B-flat major]] by [[Joseph Haydn]].<ref>p. 265 (1974) Hugues</ref> The {{lang|la|[[missa brevis]]}} (short mass) was written around 1775 for the order of the {{lang|de|Barmherzige Br\u00fcder}} ([[Brothers Hospitallers of St. John of God|Brothers Hospitallers]]) in [[Eisenstadt]], whose [[patron saint]] was [[John of God]]. Scored modestly for soprano, four-part mixed choir, two violins, organ and bass, it is known as the '''Kleine Orgelmesse''' ('''Little Organ Mass''') due to an extended organ solo in the Benedictus movement.\n\n== History ==\nHaydn composed four or five short masses, depending on the ''Missa brevis Rorate coeli desuper'' being composed by him or not. The ''Missa brevis Sancti Joannis de Deo'' is his last {{lang|la|[[missa brevis]]}}. All these short masses share a modest orchestra.<ref name=\"MacIntyre\" />\n\nThe mass was written for the order of the {{lang|de|Barmherzige Br\u00fcder}}, also called Brothers of Mercy, in [[Eisenstadt]], [[Hungarian Kingdom]] (now Austria), whose founder and [[patron saint]] was St. [[John of God]].<ref name=\"Hyperion\">{{cite web| url = http://www.hyperion-records.co.uk/dw.asp?dc=W2581_66508 | title = Missa Brevis Sancti Joannis de Deo 'Small Organ Mass', Hob XXII:7 | publisher = [[Hyperion Records|Hyperion]] | accessdate = 22 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"p. blank 1989 McCaldin\">p. [blank] (1989) McCaldin</ref><ref name=\"p. blank 1989 McCaldin\"/> Haydn lived in Eisenstadt, working for the court of [[Nikolaus II, Prince Esterh\u00e1zy]]. The composition was written in 1774.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Alwes|first=Chester|title=A History of Western Choral Music: Volume 1|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=336}}</ref> Because of an extensive [[Organ (music)|Organ]] solo in the Benedictus, it is known as the Kleine Orgelmesse (Little Organ Mass),<ref name=\"Hyperion\" /> referring to the {{Interlanguage link multi|Missa in honorem Beatissimae Virginis Mariae|de|3=Gro\u00dfe Orgelsolomesse|lt=Gro\u00dfe Orgelsolomesse}} (Great Organ Mass), a colloquial name for the ''Missa in honorem Beatissimae Virginis Mariae'', Haydn's fourth mass in [[E-flat major]]. An organ solo in the Benedictus was common practice at the time.<ref name=\"MacIntyre\" />\n\nHaydn played the organ in the first performance,<ref name=\"Hsu\">{{cite web|url=http://atlantabaroque.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/2007-05-13-program.pdf|title=Handel and Haydn|last=Hsu|first=John|date=13 May 2007|publisher=atlantabaroque.org|accessdate=22 August 2015}}</ref> in the hospital chapel of the Brethren in Eisenstadt. \"Kleine\" (little) may refer to the composition as well as to the organ, because the instrument  there was a positive with six stops without pedal.<ref name=\"MacIntyre\" />\n\n== Scoring and structure ==\nThe setting of the [[Latin]] mass is structured in six movements. It was originally scored for a solo soprano, a four-part choir ([[SATB]]), the so-called ''{{lang|de|Wiener Kirchentrio}}'' (Vienna church trio) of two violins and bass, with an organ which has a solo function in the Benedictus.<ref name=\"Hyperion\" /><ref name=\"Morrison\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/composition/mc0002361608|title=Franz Joseph Haydn / Missa brevis St. Joannis de Deo, for soloists, chorus, organ & orchestra in B flat major (\"Little Organ Mass\"), H. 22/7|last=Morrison|first=Chris|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=22 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the following table of the movements, the voices, markings, [[Key (music)|keys]] and [[time signature]]s are taken from the choral score.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | No.\n! scope=\"col\" | Part\n! scope=\"col\" | Incipit\n! scope=\"col\" | Vocal\n! scope=\"col\" | Marking\n! scope=\"col\" | Key\n! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n| 1 || style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{lang|grc|[[#Kyrie|Kyrie]]}} || {{lang|grc|Kyrie}} || SATB || {{lang|it|Adagio}} || B-flat major || {{music|common-time}}\n|-\n| 2 || style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{lang|la|[[#Gloria|Gloria]]}} || {{lang|la|Gloria}} || SATB || {{lang|it|Allegro molto}} || B-flat major || 3/4\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 3 || rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{lang|la|[[#Credo|Credo]]}} || {{lang|la|Credo}} || SATB  || {{lang|it|Allegro}} || rowspan=\"3\" | B-flat major || {{music|common-time}}\n|-\n| {{lang|la|Et incarnatus est}} || SATB || {{lang|it|Adagio}} || rowspan=\"2\" | 3/4\n|-\n| {{lang|la|Et resurrexit}} || SATB || {{lang|it|Allegro}}\n|-\n| 4 || style=\"text-align: center;\"| {{lang|la|[[#Sanctus|Sanctus]]}} || {{lang|la|Sanctus}} || SATB || {{lang|it|Allegro}} || B-flat major || 6/8\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 5 || rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{lang|la|[[#Benedictus|Benedictus]]}} || {{lang|la|Benedictus}} || Soprano || {{lang|it|Moderato}} || E-flat major || {{music|common-time}}\n|-\n| {{lang|la|Osanna}} || SATB || {{lang|it|Allegro}} || B-flat major || 6/8\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 6 || style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{lang|la|[[#Agnus Dei|Agnus Dei]]}} || {{lang|la|Agnus Dei}} || SATB || {{lang|it|Adagio}} || B-flat major || 3/4\n|-\n|}\n\n== Music ==\nThe movements Gloria and Credo are kept extremely short by the technique of {{lang|de|{{Interlanguage link multi|Polytextur|de}}}} (multiple texts): \"several clauses of the text [are set] simultaneously in different voices.\"<ref name=\"Hyperion\" /><ref>p. 125 (1974) Hugues</ref> The texts from the order of mass are repeated in every mass and thus well known; The setting of different passages assigned to the different parts, heard simultaneously, does justice to the liturgy but keeps the music short. The Benedictus is the only movement which is not in B-flat major, and set for a solo voice.\n\n=== Kyrie ===\nThe Kyrie shows, according to the musicologist John Hsu \"brilliant instrumental idioms and choral declamation.<ref name=\"Hsu\" />\n<!--\n=== Gloria === -->\n\n=== Credo ===\nThe Credo is structured in three parts, the center being formed by an Adagio for the birth, suffering and death of Jesus, delivered by the choir mostly in [[homophony]], accompanied by broken chords in the violins and repetition in the bass. The third section recapitulates music from the Gloria.<ref name=\"Hsu\" />\n\n=== Sanctus ===\nSanctus is called by the voices in a fast sequence of entries, some as bell-like long notes, other in flowing triplets. For the Osanna, the voices enter from the lowest to the highest, only one measure apart. The instruments play [[colla parte]] with the voices, violins with soprano and alto, cello and [[violone]] with the bass.<ref name=\"Hsu\" />\n\n=== Benedictus ===\nThe Benedictus, the longest movement, is a dialogue of soprano soloist and organ, described as \"expressive, elegant, and ornate melodic lines\". It is followed by a repeat of the Osanna.<ref name=\"Hsu\" />\n\n=== Agnus Dei ===\nHaydn marked the Agnus Dei carefully for dramatic contrast in dynamics, setting \"Agnus Dei\" (Lamb of God) as a [[fortissimo]] homophonic call versus a [[Dynamics (music)|pianissimo]] prayer \"Dona nobis pacem\" (Give us peace).<ref name=\"Hsu\" /> The end is marked \"[[perdendosi]], senza organo\" (dying away, without organ), with a [[pizzicato]] bass.<ref name=\"MacIntyre\" />\n\nA reviewer of the Oxford edition summarized: \"The work is accessible to most choirs. The music is not excessively difficult, but the solid musical structure and the many passages requiring expressive singing make\nthe work a rewarding pleasure for any size choir.<ref name=\"MacIntyre\" /> [[H. C. Robbins Landon]], an editor of the composition, ascribed to the work a \"quiet spirit of devotion, even of mysticism, that is most appealing\".<ref name=\"Hyperion\" />\n\n== Versions ==\n\nWhile the mass was originally scored for choir, strings and organ, later versions include with [[trumpet]]s and [[timpani]], and [[clarinet]]s.<ref name=\"Hyperion\" />\n\nThe mass was also used in Salzburg where the textual compression was deemed \"unacceptable\", therefore the composer's brother [[Michael Haydn]] expanded the Gloria, from 31 measures to 118.<ref name=\"p. blank 1989 McCaldin\"/> Very few performances however, use this expansion. However, the [[Oxford University Press|Oxford edition]] presents Michael Haydn's prolongation in the main body of the text and Joseph's short original as an appendix.<ref name=\"MacIntyre\">{{cite web | last = MacIntyre | first = Bruce C. | jstor = 942089 | title = Joseph Haydn. Missa brevis SanctiJoannis de Deo (Hob. XXII:7) \"Little Organ Mass\" with Michael Haydn's prolongation of the Gloria. Edited by Denis McCaldin. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1989. | publisher = Music Library Association }}</ref><ref name=\"p. blank 1989 McCaldin\"/><ref>p. 458 (1989) Aston</ref> [[Johann Georg Albrechtsberger]] wrote an alternate Benedictus.<ref name=\"Hyperion\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Aston (1989) Peter. \"Review\" August ''Music & Letters'' No. 3, Vol. 70\n* Hugues (1974) Rosemary. London. ''Haydn''. J. M. Dent & Sons Ltd\n* McCaldin (1989) Denis. Introduction. Oxford. Franz Joseph Haydn: Missa brevis Sancti Joannis de Deo, Hob. XXII:7, Little Organ Mass, with prolongation by Michael Haydn. Oxford University Press\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{IMSLP2|work=Mass in B-flat major, Hob.XXII:7 (Haydn, Joseph)|cname=Mass in B-flat major, Hob.XXII:7}}\n* {{ChoralWiki|Kleine_Orgelmesse_(Mass_no._7_in_Bb_Major)_(Franz_Joseph_Haydn)|Missa brevis Sancti Joannis de Deo}}\n* Jones, Jill Ann: [http://scholarworks.sjsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1840&context=etd_theses A Historical Study of Joseph Haydn's Missa brevis Sancti Joannis de Deo Hob XXII:7] [[San Jose State University]] 1994\n\n{{Haydn masses}}\n\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Missa Brevis Sancti Joannis De Deo}}\n[[Category:Masses by Joseph Haydn]]\n[[Category:Music for orchestra and organ]]\n[[Category:1775 compositions]]\n[[Category:Compositions in B-flat major]]\n", "name_user": "Alicia.raquel.villarreal", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Missa_brevis_Sancti_Joannis_de_Deo"}
{"title_page": "J\u00f3zef Retinger", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Polish diplomat and activist}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger\n|image             = File:Jozef Retinger.jpg\n|image_size        = \n|caption           = J\u00f3zef Retinger, recovering from a poisoning attempt c.1944<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n|birth_date        = {{birth date|1888|04|17|df=y}}\n|birth_place       = [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]]\n|death_date        = {{death date and age|df=yes|1960|06|12|1888|04|17}}\n|death_place       = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|citizenship       = Polish\n|nationality       = Polish\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = Economics, international relations, politics\n|work_institutions = [[Sorbonne University]] Phd, [[London School of Economics]], [[Polish government-in-exile]]\n|doctoral_advisor  =\n|doctoral_students =\n|known_for         = [[Bilderberg Group]], [[European Movement International]]\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo =\n|influences        = [[Jesuits]], [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]]\n|influenced        = [[Joseph Conrad]], foundation of [[European Union]], the [[Bilderberg Group]]\n|prizes            = [[Nobel Peace Prize]] Nomination 1958\n|footnotes         =\n|signature         =\n}}\n'''J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger''' ([[Krak\u00f3w]], 17 April 1888 {{spaced ndash}} 12 June 1960, [[London]]; [[World War II]] [[nom de guerre|noms de guerre]] ''Salamandra'', \"Salamander\", and ''Brzoza'', \"Birch Tree\") was a [[Poles|Polish]] diplomat, international political adviser and activist, and writer.<ref name = \"JR\">{{cite book|title=Joseph Retinger - Memoirs of an Eminence Grise|editor=John Pomian|publisher=Sussex University Press/ Chatto & Windus|date= 1972|url=https://ia800905.us.archive.org/5/items/MemoirsOfAnEminenceGrise1972/Memoirs%20of%20an%20Eminence%20Grise%2C%201972.pdf}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War I]], Retinger was politically active in [[Austria-Hungary]] and Russia on behalf of the Polish independence movement. After the [[Russian Revolution]], he had to retreat to [[Central America]], where he became an economic adviser. After the outbreak of  [[World War II]], he was principal adviser to the [[Polish government-in-exile]].<ref name=\"Oleks\">{{cite web|title=The Most Mysterious Man in 20th-Century Politics|author=Oleksiak, Wojciech|publisher=Culture.pl|date=2016-12-14|url=https://culture.pl/en/article/the-most-mysterious-man-in-20th-century-politics|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> A Freemason with a reputation as a [[grey eminence]], he went on to cofound the [[European Movement]], which led to establishment of the [[European Union]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pieczewski|first1=Andrzej|title=Joseph Retinger's conception of and contribution to the early process of European integration|journal=European Review of History|date=11 Aug 2010|volume=17|issue=4|pages=581\u2013604|doi=10.1080/13507486.2010.495766}}</ref> and was instrumental in forming the [[Bilderberg Group]]. In 1958 he was nominated for the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Emilian Czyrnia\u0144ski.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Emilian Czyrnia\u0144ski]], Retinger's maternal grandfather, 1878 photo by [[Walery Rzewuski]]]]\n[[File:Wierchy-1925---W\u0142adys\u0142aw-Zamoyski-(1853-1924).png|thumb|150px|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]] (1853-1924)]]\n[[File:Misa Sert.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Misia Sert|Misia Godebska Sert]], Retinger's Parisian cousin]]\nJ\u00f3zef Retinger was born in [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Poland]] (then part of [[Austria-Hungary]]), the youngest of five children: his father had a daughter, Aniela, from a first marriage to Helena Jawornicka.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\">{{cite web|title=J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|url=https://kangur.uek.krakow.pl//biblioteka/retinger/B.%20Podgorski%20-%20J.H.%20Retinger%201888-1960.pdf|lang=pl|page=5|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> His mother was Maria Krystyna [[Emil Czyrnia\u0144ski|Czyrnia\u0144ska]], daughter of a [[Greek Catholic Church|Greek Catholic]] [[Lemkos|Lemko]] professor of chemistry at the [[Jagiellonian University]]. His father, J\u00f3zef Stanis\u0142aw Retinger, was the personal legal counsel and successful adviser to French-born Count [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]]. Retinger's great grandfather, Filip Rettinger, was a Jewish tailor from [[Tarn\u00f3w]] who with his family converted to Catholicism in 1827.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Sypek, Antoni|title=\u017bydowskie konwersje na chrze\u015bcija\u0144stwo w Tarnowie, w latach 1785-1900|journal= Rocznik Tarnowski|date= 2013| page= 128|trans-title= Jewish conversions to christianity in Tarn\u00f3w in 1785-1900}} </ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Minakowski, Marek Jerzy.|title=Tw\u00f3rca UE M\u0105\u017c Krewnej Kaczy\u0144skiego to \u017byd z D\u0119bicy|lang=pl|url=https://minakowski.pl/tworca-ue-maz-krewnej-kaczynskiego-to-zyd-z-debicy/|access-date=2020-03-03|trans-title=The Creator of the European Union the Husband of Kaczy\u0144ski's Relative was a Jew from D\u0119bica}}</ref> When his lawyer grandson died, Count Zamoyski took the promising youngster, J\u00f3zef, into his household and paid for him to attend the [[Bart\u0142omiej Nowodworski High School]] in Krak\u00f3w. Retinger's eldest brother, Emil, became a commander in the [[Polish Navy]], while his son, {{Interlanguage link|Witold Retinger|pl}}, was stationed in the [[United Kingdom]] during [[World War II]] (1943-45), as a member then leader of [[No. 308 Polish Fighter Squadron|Squadron 308]] of the [[Polish Air Forces in France and Great Britain|Polish Air Force]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafweb.org/Squadrons/Sqn300-318.htm|title=History of No.'s 300\u2013318 Squadrons at RAF Web|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Retinger's brother, Juliusz, taught [[physiological chemistry]] at the [[University of Chicago]] and [[University of Wilno]].<ref>{{cite book|title=[[Polish Biographical Dictionary]]|volume= 127|page= 152|lang=pl}}</ref> Retinger himself initially considered a career in the priesthood, but three months in the Jesuit [[novitiate]] in [[Rome]] confirmed he would not be suited to the life.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n\nFurther financed by Count Zamoyski in 1906, Retinger entered simultaneously the [[Ecole des sciences politiques]] and the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] in [[Paris]] and two years later, aged twenty, became the youngest person ever to earn a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in literature from there.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> While in the French capital, armed with introductions from Zamoyski and his own relative, the salonni\u00e8re and pianist [[Misia Sert]], he moved in intellectual circles and was befriended by among others, [[Andr\u00e9 Gide]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Mauriac]], [[Bernard Grasset]], [[Jean Giraudoux]], [[Erik Satie]] and [[Maurice Ravel]]. His early literary ambitions were stopped in their tracks when he presented his first novel, ''\"Les Souffleurs\"'' to Andr\u00e9 Gide for his opinion. Gide told him: ''Joseph, you will never be a writer.''<ref name = \"JR\"/>{{rp|pages=11\u201313}} \n\nHe next went to [[Munich]] to study [[comparative psychology]] for a year. From there, encouraged by Zamoyski, in 1910 he moved to [[England]], where he entered the [[London School of Economics]] for a year's study and began a lobbying operation on behalf of the Polish cause and its populations scattered across three ailing empires. Formally he became Director of the London Office of the Polish National Committee (1912\u20131914).<ref>{{cite web|title=Jozef Retinger - cv|url=https://www.cvce.eu/en/obj/joseph_retinger-en-9d454c22-957c-49ef-8c7b-be5f98d676fc.htmlE|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|first1=Wojciech|last1=Roszkowski|first2=Jan|last2=Kofman|title=Biographical Dictionary of Central and Eastern Europe in the Twentieth Century|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date=2016|isbn=9781317475934|chapter-url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=RnKlDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA2377|access-date=2017-07-25|chapter=Retinger J\u00f3zef}}</ref> During this time he continued to move in \u00e9lite circles and  thanks to an introduction by [[Arnold Bennett]] whom he had met in Paris, Retinger developed a close friendship with his older Polish compatriot, the already well established novelist, [[Joseph Conrad]].<ref name=\":0\"/> Retinger urged Conrad to visit Poland, and on 28 July 1914, the day [[World War I]] broke out, Retinger, his wife Otolia, and Conrad, his wife, and their two sons arrived in Krak\u00f3w, the two men's childhood stamping grounds (they were alumni of the same [[secondary school]]). Due to the closeness of the Russian border (Russia was then allied to Great Britain), the Conrads soon sought greater safety in the [[Tatra Mountains]] resort of [[Zakopane]].<ref>[[Zdzis\u0142aw Najder]], ''Joseph Conrad: A Life'', Rochester, New York, Camden House, 2007, {{ISBN|978-1-57113-347-2}}, pp. 459\u201363.</ref> Retinger would write about Conrad in his 1943 book, ''Conrad and His Contemporaries''. Historian [[Norman Davies]] suggests that it was probably Conrad who introduced the \"polyglot and polymath\" Retinger to the British intelligence services.<ref name=\"Davies\">{{cite book|author=Davies, Norman|title=Rising '44: The Battle for Warsaw|title-link=Rising '44|year=2003|place= London|publisher= Pan Books|isbn=0-333-90568-7| page= 53}}</ref> Later Retinger became a personal friend of Major-General Sir [[Colin Gubbins]], wartime head of [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]], and after the war an [[Special Intelligence Service|MI6]] \"asset\".<ref name=\"wilford\">{{cite book|title=The CIA, the British Left and the Cold War: Calling the Tune? Studies in Intelligence|author= Wilford, Hugh|publisher=Routledge|date= 2013|page=242|isbn=978-1135294779}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dorril, Stephen|title= A Critical Review: MI6: Fifty years of special operations. Doctoral thesis|publisher= University of Huddersfield|date=2010|url=http://eprints.hud.ac.uk/id/eprint/9763/1/sdorrilfinalthesis.pdf|page=27}}</ref>\n\n===World War I===\n[[File:Joseph Conrad author.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Joseph Conrad]]]]\nWith the clouds of war closing in, the project of writing a play together with Conrad based on the latter's novel, ''[[Nostromo]]'' had to be abandoned as both men hurriedly left Austria Hungary. Retinger would have been eligible for military call up in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]], but no mention of this is made by his biographers. Instead, he put aside literary endeavours and once more assumed the role of a political lobbyist for Poland, publishing pamphlets and travelling between London, Paris and [[New York City|New York]], aided by Conrad in London.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=10}} In the first years of the war, this was not on the agenda of the major powers. Retinger looked instead for other potential alliances and political leverage which led to meetings with leading [[Zionism|Zionists]] of the time, including [[Chaim Weizmann]], [[Vladimir Zhabotinski]] and [[Nahum Sokolow]] who were seeking international recognition and rights for the [[Jewish diaspora]].<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=11}} In 1916 guided by Zamoyski and with the approval of [[Herbert Asquith]], [[David Lloyd George]] and [[Georges Clemenceau]] with his old Parisian connections, [[Prince Sixtus of Bourbon-Parma|Sixtus]] and [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Xavier de Bourbon Parme]], the Duchess of Montebello and Marquis [[Boni de Castellane]], as well as Zamoyski's friend the Polish [[General of the Jesuits]], [[Wlodimir Led\u00f3chowski|W\u0142odzimierz Led\u00f3chowski]], Retinger became a \"courier\" in the secretive European dynastic negotiation suing for peace with Austria. It became known as the ''[[Sixtus Affair]]'' but was a failure, due to Germany's refusal to cooperate thus making Austria more dependent on it.<ref>{{cite book|title=Informal Alliance: The Bilderberg Group and Transatlantic Relations during the Cold War, 1952-1968|series=  \nRoutledge Studies in Modern History|author=Gijswijt, Thomas W.|chapter=J\u00f3zef Retinger - Informal diplomat|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date= 2018|isbn=978-1-3511-8102-0}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1 = Demblin, August | author2 = Demblin, Alexander | title = Minister gegen Kaiser : Aufzeichnungen eines \u00f6sterreichisch-ungarischen Diplomaten \u00fcber Aussenminister Czernin und Kaiser Karl |lang= de| date = 1997 | publisher = B\u00f6hlau | place = Vienna | isbn = 3-205-98762-4 | trans-title=Minister versus Kaiser: The designs of an Austro-Hungarian Diplomat to outwit Foreign Minister Czernin and [[Charles I of Austria|Kaiser Charles]]}}</ref> In 1917 he met [[Boy Capel|Arthur \"Boy\" Capel]], the half-French dilettante, polo player and \"sponsor\" of [[Coco Chanel]]. Capel is said to have planted in Retinger's mind the idea of a world federal government based on an Anglo-French alliance.<ref>{{cite journal|author= Biskupski, M. B.|title= Spy, Patriot or Internationalist? The Early Career of J\u00f3zef Retinger, Polish Patriarch of the European Union|journal= The Polish Review, Vol. 43, No. 1|date= 1998|pages= 23\u201367}}</ref> After concerns for his personal safety due to his \"political meddling\" in Austria-Hungary and in the emergent [[Soviet Union]], in 1918 Retinger was banned from France, and sought sanctuary in [[Spain]] for several months.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=12}}\n\n==Mexican years==\n[[File:Jane Anderson 1917.JPG|thumb|left|150px|US journalist [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]] 1917]] \nHe travelled on to [[Cuba]] and then to [[Mexico]], where he became an unofficial political adviser to union organizer [[Luis Morones]] whom he fortuitously met crossing the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]], and to President [[Plutarco El\u00edas Calles]].<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/><ref name=\"Oleks\"/> A glimpse of Retinger, newly divorced and love lorn for the American journalist, [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]], appears in the biography of another American woman, the communist sympathiser [[Katherine Anne Porter]], a member of the Morones circle. In it he is described as a \"Polish intriguer\" and \"British Marxist\". In 1921 while on an obscure mission to the [[United States]] to buy saddles, Retinger was arrested and imprisoned in [[Laredo, Texas|Laredo]] and Porter was despatched from Mexico to get him released.<ref name= \"Stout\">{{cite book|title=Katherine Anne Porter: A Sense of the Times - Minds of the new South|author=Stout, Janis P.|publisher=University of Virginia Press|date= 1995|pages=47-51|isbn= 978-0-813915685}}</ref> That same year Retinger had proposed that Katherine Porter and her friend Mary Doherty accompany him to Europe to do \"collaborative work\", an offer that was spurned.<ref name= \"Stout\"/>{{rp|pages=94-95}} Retinger helped advance Mexico's nationalization of its oil industry in 1928.<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\">{{cite journal|author=Ethridge, Marcus E.|title= Review of [[M.B.B. Biskupski]], \"War and Diplomacy in East and West: A Biography of J\u00f3zef Retinger\", London, Routledge, 2017, ISBN: 978-1-138-21845-1|journal= [[The Polish Review]]| volume= 64, no. 1|date= 2019| page= 95}} Ethridge's full review is on pp. 94\u201395</ref> His activities in Mexico lasted a total of almost seven years and only ended with Calles's fall from power in 1936. They inspired Retinger to write three volumes on the tumultuous events of that Latin American republic.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/> The Mexican years were punctuated by trips back to Europe where he took on the role of Representative in the United Kingdom of the Polish Socialist Party (1924\u20131928). In 1926 he married his second wife, Stella, with whom he travelled to Mexico on one occasion. After her death in 1933 his two daughters were left in the care of their maternal grandmother and were estranged from him until the 1950s.\n\nIn the rest of the interwar period, he published many contributions in periodicals, such as the Polish ''Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie'' (Literary News), on literary and political subjects.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n\n==Building blocks on the table==\n[[File:W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski, 1923.jpg|thumb|150px|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]], Polish prime minister in 1923]]\nDuring [[World War II]], Retinger who was in [[London]], was involved in arranging for Polish troops to be transferred to Britain from France. He was bidden by Winston Churchill personally to escort [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]] by plane to England from France which had just capitulated to the invading Germans.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=16}} He became principal adviser and confidant to the Prime Minister of the [[Polish Government in Exile]] now re-established in London.<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>{{rp|page= 95}}<ref>{{cite web|title=London Gazette|date=1942-12-04|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/35811/page/5301/data.pdf|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> In fact, their political relationship went back to 1916 and was strengthened during [[Wladyslaw Sikorski]]'s earlier brief stint as prime minister, 1922-23 in newly independent Poland, and came to greater fruition when both men were later in exile in London.<ref name=\"Lane\">{{cite book|title=Poland and European Integration: The Ideas and Movements of Polish Exiles in the West, 1939\u201391|author1=Lane, Thomas |author2=Wolanski, Marian|publisher=Springer|date= 2009|page=18|isbn=978-0-2302-71784}}</ref>\n\nSikorski's dependence on Retinger was the greater as he did not have mastery of [[English language|English]]. At this time Retinger was despatched to talk with other exiled government representatives in London, who included [[Marcel-Henri Jaspar]], [[Paul Van Zeeland]], [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] in preparation for a post-war geopolitical landscape.<ref>{{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1|page=455}}</ref> He went on to posit a \"Sikorski Plan\" consisting of two stages, the first of which was signed in January 1942 and proposed a Polish-Czech confederation.<ref>{{cite book|author=Walter Lipgens|title=Documents on the history of European integration: Plans for European union in Great Britain and in exile, 1939\u20131945 (including 107 documents in their original languages on 3 microfiches)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X3TsVCAt9F4C&pg=PA648|accessdate=10 August 2011|year=1985|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-009724-5|page=648}}</ref> The idea was to expand it into a [[wikt:Central Europe|Central Europe]]an confederation with Poland and [[Lithuania]], [[Czechoslovakia]] as its nucleus around which would be grouped [[Romania]], [[Hungary]], Yugoslavia and [[Greece]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Schmidt, Andrea|title=From Intermarium to the Three Seas Initiative: The Implications of the Polish Orientation Over the Central and Eastern European Region on Hungarian Policy in Baltic-Black Sea Regionalisms: Patchworks and Networks at Europe's Eastern Margins|editor1=Bogdanova, Olga |editor2=Makarychev, Andrey|publisher=Springer Nature|date= 2019|page=157|isbn= 978-3-0302-48789}}</ref> The agenda behind this was to create a common political blue-print for smaller countries abutting larger European powers and became the basis of a Belgian-Dutch union which would mirror the Polish-Czech arrangement.\n\nThis scheme of Retinger's caused problems between London and [[Moscow]]. In order not to tread on Soviet toes, the British altered their position and refused to back Sikorski's negotiations with the eight smaller European states. In his speech on the Council of Europe, [[Winston Churchill]] [https://www.winstonchurchill.org/resources/speeches/1941-1945-war-leader/national-address/ BBC radio broadcast] on 21 March 1943 referred to the necessity of smaller nations forming groupings, but that it was too early to go into detail. The most Retinger was able to achieve was to push through the [[Sikorski-Mayski Agreement]], signed on 30 July 1941, which provided for the formation of the [[Anders' army]], thus ridding Stalin of the immediate human problem posed by the hundreds of thousands of Polish [[Prisoner of war|POW]]s and deportees from the [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u201345)|Soviet occupied]] [[Kresy Zachodnie|Kresy]] regions of the former [[Second Polish Republic]], who after an arduous odyssey across thousands of miles would eventually end up as the [[United Kingdom]]'s human problem.<ref>{{cite book|author=Anders, Lt.-General W\u0142adys\u0142aw|title= An Army in Exile|publisher= MacMillan & Co. Ltd|date=1949|page=73}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Polish Underground Army, the Western Allies, and the Failure of Strategic Unity in World War II|author=Peszke, Michael Alfred|publisher=McFarland|date= 2015|isbn=978-1-4766-10276|page=70}}</ref> This trade-off adumbrated the [[Tehran Conference|Tehran]] and [[Yalta Conference]]s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Identity in Flux. The Polish Community in Britain|author=Sword, Keith|place=London|publisher=School of Slavonic and East European Studies - SSEES Occasional Papers No. 36| date=1996|isbn=0-903425-60-2|pages=24\u201330|url=https://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/id/eprint/10078280/1/SSEES0012.pdf|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Brushes with death==\nRetinger narrowly avoided perishing in the sea off [[Gibraltar]] with [[Wladyslaw Sikorski's death controversy|W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]], in July 1943, but for the fact that he was not needed to accompany the premier on a troop inspection in the Middle East and would be better employed in London. The spare seat on the plane went to Sikorski's daughter who died with her father.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> Retinger was devastated by this turn of events. His relationship with Sikorski's successor, [[Stanislaw Mikolajczyk]] was much more ambivalent, but he obtained his consent for a special mission to Poland under [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]] in April 1944.<ref>Bu\u0142hak, W\u0142adys\u0142aw. \"The Foreign Office and the [[Special Operations Executive]] and the Expedition of J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger to Poland, April\u2013July 1944\", ''[[The Polish Review]]'', vol. 61, no. 3, 2016, pp. 33\u201357.</ref>\n\nWith an SOE brief and without prior training, Retinger, aged 56, parachuted into [[German-occupied Poland|occupied Poland]] with 2nd Lt. [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt]], (see [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt#Operation \"Salamander\"|Operation Salamander]]), to meet with Polish underground figures, to deliver money to the Polish underground, and to \"explain to his fellow Poles in the homeland 'how are we going to lose this war'\".<ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\">{{cite book|last1=Eringer|first1=Robert|author-link=Robert Eringer|title=The Global Manipulators|publisher=Pentacle Books|asin=B00546KTEM|oclc=26551991}}</ref>{{rp|pages=16\u201322}} <ref name = \"JR\"/>{{rp|page=265}}<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>  Following at least one assassination attempt on him, Retinger expressed his frustration thus:\n\n{{blockquote|You know why I came.  The [Underground] [[Government Delegation for Poland|Delegate]] knows as well.... They know that I only want to convince them that it will be necessary in the future to cooperate with the Communists, because no English are coming here, only Russians.  If we do not get along with them somehow, it will be a terrible tragedy, because we well know what [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]] and the [[NKVD]] [Interior Ministry of the Soviet Union] are. And it's about trying to make people here understand this fact. And they want to murder me!}}<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>\n\nThe latter quip was a reference to elements in the [[Polish Underground Army]], the [[Armia Krajowa|AK]] who were convinced Retinger was not serving the interests of his country and should therefore be \"removed\". One apparent attempt to liquidate him in Poland was on the grounds of a \"death sentence\" to be carried out on the alleged orders of general [[Kazimierz Sosnkowski]]. It was foiled by the intervention of an old friend and [[Armia Krajowa|AK fighter]], Tadeusz Gebethner.<ref>{{cite web|title=The story of Tadeusz Gebethner|url=https://sprawiedliwi.org.pl/en/stories-of-rescue/story-tadeusz-gebethner|publisher=sprawiedliwi.org.pl |access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> There was also an attempt during his visit in occupied Poland to poison him, which failed. On his return to London, he spent some time in the [[Dorchester Hotel]] in London's [[Park Lane, London|Park Lane]] recovering from his ordeal of the trip, which left him lame in one leg for the rest of his life, possibly due to the [[Polyneuritis]] brought on by the poison. His first visitor at the Dorchester was Sir [[Anthony Eden]], the foreign secretary.<ref name=\"Davies\"/><ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\"/>\n\n==Vision for Europe==\n[[File:Krakow-Jozef Retinger plaque.jpg|thumb|right|[[Krak\u00f3w]] plaque commemorating Retinger, \"great pioneer of European unity\".]]\nAfter World War II, Retinger feared another devastating war in Europe, this time fought between \"Russia\" and \"the Anglo-Saxons\".<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/> He became a leading advocate of [[European unification]] as a means of securing peace.<ref>{{cite web|author=Retinger, J. H.|title= The European Continent? Address given to the Royal Institute of Foreign Affairs in London|url=https://www.cvce.eu/content/publication/2008/2/19/534c684a-8924-445a-8181-58360f939f56/publishable_en.pdf|publisher=CVCE|date= 7 May 1946|access-date=2020-03-27}} Correction: although the original states Royal Institute of Foreign Affairs, it should read [[Royal Institute of International Affairs]], known today as \"[[Chatham House]]\", this is likely a copyediting error at CVCE (ed.).</ref> He helped found both the [[European Movement]] and the [[Council of Europe]], somewhat to the dismay of the philosopher Count [[Richard Coudenhove-Kalergi]], the post-[[World War I]] [[Anti-communism|anti-bolshevist]] founder of the [[Paneuropean Union]] movement.<ref>{{cite book|title=The CIA, the British Left and the Cold War: Calling the Tune? Studies in Intelligence|author= Wilford, Hugh|publisher=Routledge|date= 2013|pages=227\u2013228|isbn=978-1135294779}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1|page=165}}</ref> \n\nRetinger, with his connections in Holland, Belgium, and [[Switzerland]] (he was a friend of [[Denis de Rougemont]]), took his cue from [[Winston Churchill]]'s 1947 [[Zurich]] speech and found fertile ground with thirteen British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] members of Parliament who backed the idea of a loose European association of states. Working in particular with Britain's [[Duncan Sandys]], incidentally Churchill's son-in-law, he took on the lion's share of the work and became Honorary Secretary General of the [[European Movement]]. He organised the 1948 [[Congress of Europe|Hague Congress]] which brought together the two camps of those for a unified Europe and those in favour of a federal Europe.<ref name=\"Lane\"/> During the congress, Retinger networked assiduously among the delegates, who included the Vatican diplomat, [[Giovanni Montini]], the future [[Pope Paul VI]]. Ensuing discussions led eventually to the formation in 1951 of a [[European Coal and Steel Community]].<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>  \n \nRetinger initiated the informal [[Bilderberg Group|Bilderberg]] conferences in 1954 and was their secretary until his premature death in London. Despite eschewing any distinctions or medals throughout his life, in 1958 he was nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.nobelprize.org/nomination/archive/show.php?id=15660 |title =Nomination for Nobel Peace Prize: Joseph Retinger |author =Nobelprize.org |publisher =Nobel Media AB 2014 |website = Nomination Database| date = |access-date = 2014-10-09}}</ref> He died in poverty of lung cancer.<ref name =\"BP\">{{cite web|title=J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|url=https://kangur.uek.krakow.pl//biblioteka/retinger/B.%20Podgorski%20-%20J.H.%20Retinger%201888-1960.pdf|lang=pl|page=53|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> He was buried at [[North Sheen Cemetery]] in the presence of five British cabinet ministers as well as of his two younger daughters who were finally reconciled with him.<ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\"/>{{rp|pages=16\u201322}} According to the oration of Sir [[Edward Beddington-Behrens]], Retinger not only had special access to [[10 Downing Street]] but also to the [[White House]].<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> \n[[File:Gr\u00f3b J\u00f3zefa Hieronima Retingera.jpg|thumb|right|Retinger's grave, [[North Sheen Cemetery]], London]]\nRetinger's long time personal assistant and the editor of his posthumous memoirs, John Pomian, actually {{Interlanguage link|Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz|pl}}, was another Polish emigr\u00e9 in London, later a director of the Heim gallery in London's [[St James's]], owned by the influential Polish art historian and philanthropist, [[Andrzej Ciechanowiecki]].<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://nekrologi.wyborcza.pl/0,11,,373783,Jan-Pomiana-B%C5%82awdziewicza-kondolencje.html | title =Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz | trans-title=Obituary of Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz|journal = nekrologi.wyborcza.pl |date=2015| lang = pl | access-date = 2016-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRetinger married twice. In 1912 he wed the well-born Otolia Zubrzycka (divorced 1921, died 1984), with whom he had a daughter, Malina. In 1926 he wed Stella Morel (died 1933), daughter of French-born pacifist and [[Dundee]] member of Parliament [[E.D. Morel]] and Mary, n\u00e9e Richardson, with whom he had two daughters, Maria and Stasia. \n\nDuring his interwar travels, Retinger fell under the spell of several women, especially the American journalist [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]], a lover of Joseph Conrad.<ref name= \"JM\">{{cite book|title=Joseph Conrad: A Biography|author= Meyers, Jeffrey|\npublisher=Rowman & Littlefield|date= 2001|page=361|isbn=978-0-8154-11123}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Athens Observer|first=Donald E.|last=Wilkes|title=Jane Anderson: The Nazi Georgia Peach|url=http://digitalcommons.law.uga.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1019&context=fac_pm|date=May 18, 1995|page=5|accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref> Retinger's own liaison with Anderson brought about the breakdown of Retinger's marriage to Otolia and drove a wedge between him and his friend Conrad.<ref name= \"JM\"/>{{rp|page=293}}\n\n==Controversy==\nOver sixty years after his death, the left-leaning Retinger continues to attract fascination and controversy with, on one hand, admirers of his political skill, his apparently selfless single-mindedness and his lasting institutional legacy in Europe and beyond.<ref>{{cite book|author=Wisnewski, Gerhard|title=The Bilderbergers Puppet-Masters of Power?: An Investigation into Claims of Conspiracy at the Heart of Politics, Business and the Media|translator=J. Collis|trans-title=Drahtzieher der Macht (2010)|date=2014|place=West Sussex|publisher=Clairview Books|isbn=978 1 90557075 1|pages=63-66}}</ref> On the other hand, detractors impugn his influence due to alleged connections with deeply secret and malign factions for which there is so far no reliable evidence.<ref>{{cite journal|author=K\u0119der, Wojciech|title=Recenzje: Bogdan Podg\u00f3rski, J\u00f3zef Retinger prywatny polityk, Universitas, Krak\u00f3w 2013, ss. 417.\n|journal=Studia Sandomierskie 23|date= 2016|pages=303-314|lang=pl|trans-title=Review of Bogdan Podg\u00f3rski, ''J\u00f3zef Retinger private politician''. Krak\u00f3w: Universitas. 2013, pages 417.|url=https://journals.indexcopernicus.com/api/file/viewByFileId/84684.pdf}}\n</ref> He remains an enigma and probably the one significant contributor to post-war European peace without a monument.<ref name = \"BP\"/>{{rp|page=60}} \n\nIn 2000 [[The Daily Telegraph]]'s [[Ambrose Evans-Pritchard]] revealed from declassified US Government records that:\n{{blockquote|The leaders of the European Movement \u2013 Retinger, the visionary [[Robert Schuman]] and the former Belgian prime minister [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] \u2013 were all treated as hired hands by their American sponsors. The US role was handled as a covert operation. ACUE\u2019s funding came from the [[Ford Foundation|Ford]] and [[Rockefeller Foundation]]s as well as business groups with close ties to the US government.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/1356047/Euro-federalists-financed-by-US-spy-chiefs.html|title=Euro-federalists financed by US Spy Chief|author= Ambrose Evans-Pritchard|date=18 September 2000|publisher= The Daily Telegraph|author-link=Ambrose Evans-Pritchard}}</ref>}} The finding, in the context of the [[Cold War]], was subsequently analysed in greater detail by ''[[Le Figaro Magazine|Le Figaro]]'' commentator, {{Interlanguage link|R\u00e9mi Kauffer|fr}} in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kauffer, R\u00e9mi|title=Quand la CIA finan\u00e7ait la construction europ\u00e9enne - Par R\u00e9mi Kauffer, Source : Historia 2003|date=12 June 2019|url=http://www.comite-valmy.org/spip.php?article516|publisher=Comit\u00e9 Valmy|lang=fr|trans-title=When the CIA financed the construction of Europe by R\u00e9mi Kauffer, source: Historia 2003|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> However, as Hugh Wilford demonstrates, the initiative to win American backing for a \"United States of Europe\" did not come either from [[Allen Dulles]], deputy, then chief of the [[CIA]], nor from Senator [[William Fulbright]], chairman of the [[ACUE]], but from the lobbying Europeans themselves guided by disparate motives, namely Coudenhove-Kalergi and Retinger who eclipsed him due to his close connection with [[Winston Churchill]] on European matters.<ref name=\"wilford\"/>\n\n== Selected works==\nBy J. H. Retinger:\n* {{cite book|date= 1908|title=Le conte fantastique dans le romantisme fran\u00e7ais|place= Gen\u00e8ve|publisher= Slatkine Reprints, 1973|trans-title=Fantastic Tales in the French Romantic Tradition}}\n* {{cite book|title=Histoire de la litt\u00e9rature fran\u00e7aise du romantisme \u00e0 nos jours|place= Paris|publisher=[[Bernard Grasset| B. Grasset]]|date= 1911|trans-title=The History of French Literature from Romanticism to the Present Day}}\n* {{cite book|title= The Poles and Prussia|place=London|date=1913|url=https://explore.library.leeds.ac.uk/special-collections-explore/334918/the_poles_and_prussia?subject=%22Polish%20question%22&resultOffset=2}} available at University of Leeds Library\n* {{cite book|title=La Pologne et l'\u00c9quilibre europ\u00e9en|place= Paris|date= 1916|trans-title=Poland and the Stability of Europe}}\n* {{cite book|title=Morones of Mexico; a history of the labour movement in that country|place=London|publisher= The Labour Pub. Co. Ltd.|date= 1926}}\n* {{cite book|title=Tierra mexicana; the history of land and agriculture in ancient and modern Mexico|place= London|publisher= N. Douglas|date= 1928}}\n* {{cite book|title=Polacy w cywilizacjach zagranicznych|trans-title= Poles in Foreign Civilizations|place=Warsaw|date= 1934}}\n* {{cite journal|title= Historja i polityka: Nowy czynnik w dyplomacji mi\u0119dzynarodowej|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie (50)|date= 4 December 1938|trans-title=History and Politics: A new factor in international diplomacy}}\n* {{cite journal|title= Historja i polityka: Zast\u00f3j w mi\u0119dzynarodowej dzia\u0142alno\u015bci Rosji|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie (51)|date= 11 December 1938|trans-title=History and Politics: Suspension of Russian activity in international relations}} \n* {{cite book|title=All about Poland: facts, figures, documents|place= London|publisher= Minerva Pub. Co.|date= 1941}}\n* {{cite book|title=Conrad and His Contemporaries |year=1942 |publisher=Roy |publication-place=New York|orig-year=First published by Minerva, London, 1941}}\n*  {{cite book|title= The European Continent? Address given to the Royal Institute of International Affairs in London|url=https://www.cvce.eu/content/publication/2008/2/19/534c684a-8924-445a-8181-58360f939f56/publishable_en.pdf|date= 7 May 1946|place=London}}\n*  {{cite book|title=The Bilderberg Group|place= Hertfordshire, UK|date= 1959}}\n*  {{cite book|title=Under Polish eyes|place=United Kingdom|publisher= Joseph Conrad Society|date= 1975}}\n\nAbout Retinger:\n* {{cite journal|author=Poraj, Stanis\u0142aw|title= \"The knight among nations\"|journal= Tydzie\u0144 Literacki Polski Zbrojnej, 2 (24)|lang=pl|date= 19 June 1938}}\n* {{cite book|author=[[Denis de Rougemont|de Rougemont, Denis]]|date= 1961|title=A Biographical Sketch. In Tribute to a Great European|editor= Retinger, J.H.|pages=20\u201350|place= Geneva|publisher= Centre Europe\u00e9ne de la Culture|lang=}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Siemaszko, Zbigniew Sebastian|date=1967|title= Retinger w Polsce 1944 r.|place=Paris|journal= Zeszyty Historyczne, 12|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|title=J\u00f3zef Retinger: Memoirs of an Eminence Grise|editor=Pomian, John|publisher= Sussex University Press/Chatto & Windus|date= 1972| isbn=0-85621-002-1|oclc=844436367}}.\n* {{cite book|author=[[Jan Nowak-Jeziora\u0144ski|Nowak, Jan]]|title= Kurier z Warszawy|place= London|publisher= Odnowa|date= 1978|lang=pl|isbn= 0-903705-37-0}}\n* {{cite book|publisher=[[Polski S\u0142ownik Biograficzny]]|title= J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|volume= XXXI|date= 1988-1989|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|title=In remembrance of Joseph Retinger 1988-1960, Initiator of the European League for Economic Cooperation|publisher= [[European League for Economic Cooperation]]|place= Brussels|date= 1996}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Grosbois, Thierry|date= 1999|title=L\u2019action de J\u00f3zef Retinger en faveur de l\u2019id\u00e9e europ\u00e9enne 1940-46|journal= [[European Review of History]] \u2013 Revue europ\u00e9enne d\u2019Historie| volume= 6 (34)|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Kalicki, W\u0142odzimierz|date=2010|title=Gracz, kt\u00f3ry budowa\u0142 Europ\u0119|trans-title=The Player who built Europe|journal= [[Gazeta Wyborcza]] no. 219|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|title= J\u00f3zef Retinger \u2013 prywatny polityk|trans-title=J\u00f3zef Retinger - a private politician|publisher= Universitas|date= 2013|isbn=97883-242-2351-0}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of governments in exile during World War II]]\n*[[European Movement]]\n*[[European Union]]\n*[[List of Poles#Diplomats|List of Poles]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=Bines, Jeffrey|title=Poland's S.O.E: A British Perspective: the Story of the Polish Country Section of the Special Operations Executive 1940-1946 Including the British Military Mission Number Four to Poland 1939|publisher=Polish Underground Movement Study Trust|date= 2018|place=London|isbn=978-0-9928-03056}} \n* {{cite journal|author= Biskupski, M.B.|title=Spy, Patriot or Internationalist? The Early Career of J\u00f3zef Retinger, Polish Patriarch of European Union|journal=[[The Polish Review]]| volume= 43, no. 1|date= 1998| pages= 23-67}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Bu\u0142hak, W\u0142adys\u0142aw|title=The Foreign Office and the [[Special Operations Executive]] and the Expedition of J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger to Poland, April\u2013July 1944|journal=The Polish Review| volume= 61, no. 3|date= 2016| pages= 33\u201357}}\n* {{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=J\u00f3zef H. Retinger \u2013 pomys\u0142odawca i wsp\u00f3\u0142tw\u00f3rca Grupy Bilderbergu|trans-title=Joseph Retinger:  Visionary Co-founder of the [[Bilderberg Group]]|lang=pl|journal= Studia polityczne|publisher= ISP PAN|volume= 10|date= 2000}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Dzia\u0142alno\u015b\u0107 J.H. Retingera na rzecz zjednoczonej Europy|trans-title=Joseph Retinger\u2019s Work for a United Europe|journal= Studia Europejskie|publisher= Centrum Europejskie Uniwersytetu Warszawskiego|volume=  16|date= 2000|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Dzia\u0142alno\u015b\u0107 J\u00f3zefa Hieronima Retingera na rzecz integracji europejskiej|lang=pl|trans-title= Joseph Retinger\u2019s Work for European Integration|publisher= Wydawnictwo Adam Marsza\u0142ek|place= Toru\u0144|date= 2008|isbn=978-83-7611-184-1}}\n* {{cite book|author= Hampson, Robert|title=Conrad's Secrets|publisher=\tPalgrave Macmillan|date= 2012|isbn=978-0-2305-0783-8}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Joseph Retinger's Vision of [a] United Europe After World War II:  Central and Eastern European Question|journal= [[The Polish Review]]| volume= 60, no 4|date= 2015 |pages= 49-66}}\n* {{cite book|author=Wisnewski, Gerhard|title=The Bilderbergers Puppet-Masters of Power?: An Investigation into Claims of Conspiracy at the Heart of Politics, Business and the Media|translator=J. Collis|trans-title=Drahtzieher der Macht (2010)|date=2014|place=West Sussex|publisher=Clairview Books|isbn=978 1 90557075 1|pages=63-66}}\n* {{cite book|title=Informal Alliance: The Bilderberg Group and Transatlantic Relations during the Cold War, 1952-1968|series=  \nRoutledge Studies in Modern History|author=Gijswijt, Thomas W.|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date= 2018|isbn=978-1-3511-8102-0}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161027232624/http://home.teleport.com/~flyheart/retinger.htm Biography of Jozef Retinger]\n*[https://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/205254911 The Polish Soviet Relations During The Second World War, photographs held by the [[Imperial War Museum]] including of Dr. J\u00f3zef Retinger on 30.07.1941]\n*[http://www.bilderberg.org/bildhist.htm#Memoirs Chapter 4, European Unity.] from ''Memoirs of An Eminence Grise'' by John Pomian,\n*[http://bilderbergmeetings.co.uk/jozef-retinger/ Bilderberg website on Retinger's life in brief]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Retinger, Jozef}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Poland to Russia]]\n[[Category:Council of Europe]]\n[[Category:Members of the Steering Committee of the Bilderberg Group]]\n[[Category:Polish politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Freemasons]]\n[[Category:European integration pioneers]]\n[[Category:Geopoliticians]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Polish diplomats]]\n[[Category:Polish spies]]\n[[Category:Secret Intelligence Service personnel]]\n[[Category:Special Operations Executive personnel]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish writers]]\n[[Category:Exophonic writers]]\n[[Category:Polish essayists]]\n[[Category:Male essayists]]\n[[Category:Polish political writers]]\n[[Category:Polish people of World War II]]\n[[Category:People of World War II]]\n[[Category:History of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Rusyn descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Polish diplomat and activist}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger\n|image             = File:Jozef Retinger.jpg\n|image_size        = \n|caption           = J\u00f3zef Retinger, recovering from a poisoning attempt c.1944<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n|birth_date        = {{birth date|1888|04|17|df=y}}\n|birth_place       = [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]]\n|death_date        = {{death date and age|df=yes|1960|06|12|1888|04|17}}\n|death_place       = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|citizenship       = Polish\n|nationality       = Polish\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = Economics, international relations, politics\n|work_institutions = [[Sorbonne University]] Phd, [[London School of Economics]], [[Polish government-in-exile]]\n|doctoral_advisor  =\n|doctoral_students =\n|known_for         = [[Bilderberg Group]], [[European Movement International]]\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo =\n|influences        = [[Jesuits]], [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]]\n|influenced        = [[Joseph Conrad]], foundation of [[European Union]], the [[Bilderberg Group]]\n|prizes            = [[Nobel Peace Prize]] Nomination 1958\n|footnotes         =\n|signature         =\n}}\n'''J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger''' ([[Krak\u00f3w]], 17 April 1888 {{spaced ndash}} 12 June 1960, [[London]]; [[World War II]] [[nom de guerre|noms de guerre]] ''Salamandra'', \"Salamander\", and ''Brzoza'', \"Birch Tree\") was a [[Poles|Polish]] diplomat, international political adviser and activist, and writer.<ref name = \"JR\">{{cite book|title=Joseph Retinger - Memoirs of an Eminence Grise|editor=John Pomian|publisher=Sussex University Press/ Chatto & Windus|date= 1972|url=https://ia800905.us.archive.org/5/items/MemoirsOfAnEminenceGrise1972/Memoirs%20of%20an%20Eminence%20Grise%2C%201972.pdf}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War I]], Retinger was politically active in [[Austria-Hungary]] and Russia on behalf of the Polish independence movement. After the [[Russian Revolution]], he had to retreat to [[Central America]], where he became an economic adviser. After the outbreak of  [[World War II]], he was principal adviser to the [[Polish government-in-exile]].<ref name=\"Oleks\">{{cite web|title=The Most Mysterious Man in 20th-Century Politics|author=Oleksiak, Wojciech|publisher=Culture.pl|date=2016-12-14|url=https://culture.pl/en/article/the-most-mysterious-man-in-20th-century-politics|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> A Freemason with a reputation as a [[grey eminence]], he went on to cofound the [[European Movement]], which led to establishment of the [[European Union]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pieczewski|first1=Andrzej|title=Joseph Retinger's conception of and contribution to the early process of European integration|journal=European Review of History|date=11 Aug 2010|volume=17|issue=4|pages=581\u2013604|doi=10.1080/13507486.2010.495766}}</ref> and was instrumental in forming the [[Bilderberg Group]]. In 1958 he was nominated for the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Emilian Czyrnia\u0144ski.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Emilian Czyrnia\u0144ski]], Retinger's maternal grandfather, 1878 photo by [[Walery Rzewuski]]]]\n[[File:Wierchy-1925---W\u0142adys\u0142aw-Zamoyski-(1853-1924).png|thumb|150px|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]] (1853-1924)]]\n[[File:Misa Sert.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Misia Sert|Misia Godebska Sert]], Retinger's Parisian cousin]]\nJ\u00f3zef Retinger was born in [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Poland]] (then part of [[Austria-Hungary]]), the youngest of five children: his father had a daughter, Aniela, from a first marriage to Helena Jawornicka.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\">{{cite web|title=J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|url=https://kangur.uek.krakow.pl//biblioteka/retinger/B.%20Podgorski%20-%20J.H.%20Retinger%201888-1960.pdf|lang=pl|page=5|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> His mother was Maria Krystyna [[Emil Czyrnia\u0144ski|Czyrnia\u0144ska]], daughter of a [[Greek Catholic Church|Greek Catholic]] [[Lemkos|Lemko]] professor of chemistry at the [[Jagiellonian University]]. His father, J\u00f3zef Stanis\u0142aw Retinger, was the personal legal counsel and successful adviser to French-born Count [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]]. Retinger's great grandfather, Filip Rettinger, was a Jewish tailor from [[Tarn\u00f3w]] who with his family converted to Catholicism in 1827.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Sypek, Antoni|title=\u017bydowskie konwersje na chrze\u015bcija\u0144stwo w Tarnowie, w latach 1785-1900|journal= Rocznik Tarnowski|date= 2013| page= 128|trans-title= Jewish conversions to christianity in Tarn\u00f3w in 1785-1900}} </ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Minakowski, Marek Jerzy.|title=Tw\u00f3rca UE M\u0105\u017c Krewnej Kaczy\u0144skiego to \u017byd z D\u0119bicy|lang=pl|url=https://minakowski.pl/tworca-ue-maz-krewnej-kaczynskiego-to-zyd-z-debicy/|access-date=2020-03-03|trans-title=The Creator of the European Union the Husband of Kaczy\u0144ski's Relative was a Jew from D\u0119bica}}</ref> When his lawyer grandson died, Count Zamoyski took the promising youngster, J\u00f3zef, into his household and paid for him to attend the [[Bart\u0142omiej Nowodworski High School]] in Krak\u00f3w. Retinger's eldest brother, Emil, became a commander in the [[Polish Navy]], while his son, {{Interlanguage link|Witold Retinger|pl}}, was stationed in the [[United Kingdom]] during [[World War II]] (1943-45), as a member then leader of [[No. 308 Polish Fighter Squadron|Squadron 308]] of the [[Polish Air Forces in France and Great Britain|Polish Air Force]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafweb.org/Squadrons/Sqn300-318.htm|title=History of No.'s 300\u2013318 Squadrons at RAF Web|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Retinger's brother, Juliusz, taught [[physiological chemistry]] at the [[University of Chicago]] and [[University of Wilno]].<ref>{{cite book|title=[[Polish Biographical Dictionary]]|volume= 127|page= 152|lang=pl}}</ref> Retinger himself initially considered a career in the priesthood, but three months in the Jesuit [[novitiate]] in [[Rome]] confirmed he would not be suited to the life.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n\nFurther financed by Count Zamoyski in 1906, Retinger entered simultaneously the [[Ecole des sciences politiques]] and the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] in [[Paris]] and two years later, aged twenty, became the youngest person ever to earn a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in literature from there.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> While in the French capital, armed with introductions from Zamoyski and his own relative, the salonni\u00e8re and pianist [[Misia Sert]], he moved in intellectual circles and was befriended by among others, [[Andr\u00e9 Gide]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Mauriac]], [[Bernard Grasset]], [[Jean Giraudoux]], [[Erik Satie]] and [[Maurice Ravel]]. His early literary ambitions were stopped in their tracks when he presented his first novel, ''\"Les Souffleurs\"'' to Andr\u00e9 Gide for his opinion. Gide told him: ''Joseph, you will never be a writer.''<ref name = \"JR\"/>{{rp|pages=11\u201313}} \n\nHe next went to [[Munich]] to study [[comparative psychology]] for a year. From there, encouraged by Zamoyski, in 1910 he moved to [[England]], where he entered the [[London School of Economics]] for a year's study and began a lobbying operation on behalf of the Polish cause and its populations scattered across three ailing empires. Formally he became Director of the London Office of the Polish National Committee (1912\u20131914).<ref>{{cite web|title=Jozef Retinger - cv|url=https://www.cvce.eu/en/obj/joseph_retinger-en-9d454c22-957c-49ef-8c7b-be5f98d676fc.htmlE|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|first1=Wojciech|last1=Roszkowski|first2=Jan|last2=Kofman|title=Biographical Dictionary of Central and Eastern Europe in the Twentieth Century|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date=2016|isbn=9781317475934|chapter-url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=RnKlDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA2377|access-date=2017-07-25|chapter=Retinger J\u00f3zef}}</ref> During this time he continued to move in \u00e9lite circles and  thanks to an introduction by [[Arnold Bennett]] whom he had met in Paris, Retinger developed a close friendship with his older Polish compatriot, the already well established novelist, [[Joseph Conrad]].<ref name=\":0\"/> Retinger urged Conrad to visit Poland, and on 28 July 1914, the day [[World War I]] broke out, Retinger, his wife Otolia, and Conrad, his wife, and their two sons arrived in Krak\u00f3w, the two men's childhood stamping grounds (they were alumni of the same [[secondary school]]). Due to the closeness of the Russian border (Russia was then allied to Great Britain), the Conrads soon sought greater safety in the [[Tatra Mountains]] resort of [[Zakopane]].<ref>[[Zdzis\u0142aw Najder]], ''Joseph Conrad: A Life'', Rochester, New York, Camden House, 2007, {{ISBN|978-1-57113-347-2}}, pp. 459\u201363.</ref> Retinger would write about Conrad in his 1943 book, ''Conrad and His Contemporaries''. Historian [[Norman Davies]] suggests that it was probably Conrad who introduced the \"polyglot and polymath\" Retinger to the British intelligence services.<ref name=\"Davies\">{{cite book|author=Davies, Norman|title=Rising '44: The Battle for Warsaw|title-link=Rising '44|year=2003|place= London|publisher= Pan Books|isbn=0-333-90568-7| page= 53}}</ref> Later Retinger became a personal friend of Major-General Sir [[Colin Gubbins]], wartime head of [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]], and after the war an [[Special Intelligence Service|MI6]] \"asset\".<ref name=\"wilford\">{{cite book|title=The CIA, the British Left and the Cold War: Calling the Tune? Studies in Intelligence|author= Wilford, Hugh|publisher=Routledge|date= 2013|page=242|isbn=978-1135294779}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dorril, Stephen|title= A Critical Review: MI6: Fifty years of special operations. Doctoral thesis|publisher= University of Huddersfield|date=2010|url=http://eprints.hud.ac.uk/id/eprint/9763/1/sdorrilfinalthesis.pdf|page=27}}</ref>\n\n===World War I===\n[[File:Joseph Conrad author.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Joseph Conrad]]]]\nWith the clouds of war closing in, the project of writing a play together with Conrad based on the latter's novel, ''[[Nostromo]]'' had to be abandoned as both men hurriedly left Austria Hungary. Retinger would have been eligible for military call up in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]], but no mention of this is made by his biographers. Instead, he put aside literary endeavours and once more assumed the role of a political lobbyist for Poland, publishing pamphlets and travelling between London, Paris and [[New York City|New York]], aided by Conrad in London.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=10}} In the first years of the war, this was not on the agenda of the major powers. Retinger looked instead for other potential alliances and political leverage which led to meetings with leading [[Zionism|Zionists]] of the time, including [[Chaim Weizmann]], [[Vladimir Zhabotinski]] and [[Nahum Sokolow]] who were seeking international recognition and rights for the [[Jewish diaspora]].<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=11}} In 1916 guided by Zamoyski and with the approval of [[Herbert Asquith]], [[David Lloyd George]] and [[Georges Clemenceau]] with his old Parisian connections, [[Prince Sixtus of Bourbon-Parma|Sixtus]] and [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Xavier de Bourbon Parme]], the Duchess of Montebello and Marquis [[Boni de Castellane]], as well as Zamoyski's friend the Polish [[General of the Jesuits]], [[Wlodimir Led\u00f3chowski|W\u0142odzimierz Led\u00f3chowski]], Retinger became a \"courier\" in the secretive European dynastic negotiation suing for peace with Austria. It became known as the ''[[Sixtus Affair]]'' but was a failure, due to Germany's refusal to cooperate thus making Austria more dependent on it.<ref>{{cite book|title=Informal Alliance: The Bilderberg Group and Transatlantic Relations during the Cold War, 1952-1968|series=  \nRoutledge Studies in Modern History|author=Gijswijt, Thomas W.|chapter=J\u00f3zef Retinger - Informal diplomat|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date= 2018|isbn=978-1-3511-8102-0}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1 = Demblin, August | author2 = Demblin, Alexander | title = Minister gegen Kaiser : Aufzeichnungen eines \u00f6sterreichisch-ungarischen Diplomaten \u00fcber Aussenminister Czernin und Kaiser Karl |lang= de| date = 1997 | publisher = B\u00f6hlau | place = Vienna | isbn = 3-205-98762-4 | trans-title=Minister versus Kaiser: The designs of an Austro-Hungarian Diplomat to outwit Foreign Minister Czernin and [[Charles I of Austria|Kaiser Charles]]}}</ref> In 1917 he met [[Boy Capel|Arthur \"Boy\" Capel]], the half-French dilettante, polo player and \"sponsor\" of [[Coco Chanel]]. Capel is said to have planted in Retinger's mind the idea of a world federal government based on an Anglo-French alliance.<ref>{{cite journal|author= Biskupski, M. B.|title= Spy, Patriot or Internationalist? The Early Career of J\u00f3zef Retinger, Polish Patriarch of the European Union|journal= The Polish Review, Vol. 43, No. 1|date= 1998|pages= 23\u201367}}</ref> After concerns for his personal safety due to his \"political meddling\" in Austria-Hungary and in the emergent [[Soviet Union]], in 1918 Retinger was banned from France, and sought sanctuary in [[Spain]] for several months.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=12}}\n\n==Mexican years==\n[[File:Jane Anderson 1917.JPG|thumb|left|150px|US journalist [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]] 1917]] \nHe travelled on to [[Cuba]] and then to [[Mexico]], where he became an unofficial political adviser to union organizer [[Luis Morones]] whom he fortuitously met crossing the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]], and to President [[Plutarco El\u00edas Calles]].<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/><ref name=\"Oleks\"/> A glimpse of Retinger, newly divorced and love lorn for the American journalist, [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]], appears in the biography of another American woman, the communist sympathiser [[Katherine Anne Porter]], a member of the Morones circle. In it he is described as a \"Polish intriguer\" and \"British Marxist\". In 1921 while on an obscure mission to the [[United States]] to buy saddles, Retinger was arrested and imprisoned in [[Laredo, Texas|Laredo]] and Porter was despatched from Mexico to get him released.<ref name= \"Stout\">{{cite book|title=Katherine Anne Porter: A Sense of the Times - Minds of the new South|author=Stout, Janis P.|publisher=University of Virginia Press|date= 1995|pages=47-51|isbn= 978-0-813915685}}</ref> That same year Retinger had proposed that Katherine Porter and her friend Mary Doherty accompany him to Europe to do \"collaborative work\", an offer that was spurned.<ref name= \"Stout\"/>{{rp|pages=94-95}} Retinger helped advance Mexico's nationalization of its oil industry in 1928.<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\">{{cite journal|author=Ethridge, Marcus E.|title= Review of [[M.B.B. Biskupski]], \"War and Diplomacy in East and West: A Biography of J\u00f3zef Retinger\", London, Routledge, 2017, ISBN: 978-1-138-21845-1|journal= [[The Polish Review]]| volume= 64, no. 1|date= 2019| page= 95}} Ethridge's full review is on pp. 94\u201395</ref> His activities in Mexico lasted a total of almost seven years and only ended with Calles's fall from power in 1936. They inspired Retinger to write three volumes on the tumultuous events of that Latin American republic.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/> The Mexican years were punctuated by trips back to Europe where he took on the role of Representative in the United Kingdom of the Polish Socialist Party (1924\u20131928). In 1926 he married his second wife, Stella, with whom he travelled to Mexico on one occasion. After her death in 1933 his two daughters were left in the care of their maternal grandmother and were estranged from him until the 1950s.\n\nIn the rest of the interwar period, he published many contributions in periodicals, such as the Polish ''Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie'' (Literary News), on literary and political subjects.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n\n==Building blocks on the table==\n[[File:W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski, 1923.jpg|thumb|150px|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]], Polish prime minister in 1923]]\nDuring [[World War II]], Retinger who was in [[London]], was involved in arranging for Polish troops to be transferred to Britain from France. He was bidden by Winston Churchill personally to escort [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]] by plane to England from France which had just capitulated to the invading Germans.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=16}} He became principal adviser and confidant to the Prime Minister of the [[Polish Government in Exile]] now re-established in London.<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>{{rp|page= 95}}<ref>{{cite web|title=London Gazette|date=1942-12-04|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/35811/page/5301/data.pdf|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> In fact, their political relationship went back to 1916 and was strengthened during [[Wladyslaw Sikorski]]'s earlier brief stint as prime minister, 1922-23 in newly independent Poland, and came to greater fruition when both men were later in exile in London.<ref name=\"Lane\">{{cite book|title=Poland and European Integration: The Ideas and Movements of Polish Exiles in the West, 1939\u201391|author1=Lane, Thomas |author2=Wolanski, Marian|publisher=Springer|date= 2009|page=18|isbn=978-0-2302-71784}}</ref>\n\nSikorski's dependence on Retinger was the greater as he did not have mastery of [[English language|English]]. At this time Retinger was despatched to talk with other exiled government representatives in London, who included [[Marcel-Henri Jaspar]], [[Paul Van Zeeland]], [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] in preparation for a post-war geopolitical landscape.<ref>{{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1|page=455}}</ref> He went on to posit a \"Sikorski Plan\" consisting of two stages, the first of which was signed in January 1942 and proposed a Polish-Czech confederation.<ref>{{cite book|author=Walter Lipgens|title=Documents on the history of European integration: Plans for European union in Great Britain and in exile, 1939\u20131945 (including 107 documents in their original languages on 3 microfiches)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X3TsVCAt9F4C&pg=PA648|accessdate=10 August 2011|year=1985|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-009724-5|page=648}}</ref> The idea was to expand it into a [[wikt:Central Europe|Central Europe]]an confederation with Poland and [[Lithuania]], [[Czechoslovakia]] as its nucleus around which would be grouped [[Romania]], [[Hungary]], Yugoslavia and [[Greece]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Schmidt, Andrea|title=From Intermarium to the Three Seas Initiative: The Implications of the Polish Orientation Over the Central and Eastern European Region on Hungarian Policy in Baltic-Black Sea Regionalisms: Patchworks and Networks at Europe's Eastern Margins|editor1=Bogdanova, Olga |editor2=Makarychev, Andrey|publisher=Springer Nature|date= 2019|page=157|isbn= 978-3-0302-48789}}</ref> The agenda behind this was to create a common political blue-print for smaller countries abutting larger European powers and became the basis of a Belgian-Dutch union which would mirror the Polish-Czech arrangement.\n\nThis scheme of Retinger's caused problems between London and [[Moscow]]. In order not to tread on Soviet toes, the British altered their position and refused to back Sikorski's negotiations with the eight smaller European states. In his speech on the Council of Europe, [[Winston Churchill]] [https://www.winstonchurchill.org/resources/speeches/1941-1945-war-leader/national-address/ BBC radio broadcast] on 21 March 1943 referred to the necessity of smaller nations forming groupings, but that it was too early to go into detail. The most Retinger was able to achieve was to push through the [[Sikorski-Mayski Agreement]], signed on 30 July 1941, which provided for the formation of the [[Anders' army]], thus ridding Stalin of the immediate human problem posed by the hundreds of thousands of Polish [[Prisoner of war|POW]]s and deportees from the [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u201345)|Soviet occupied]] [[Kresy Zachodnie|Kresy]] regions of the former [[Second Polish Republic]], who after an arduous odyssey across thousands of miles would eventually end up as the [[United Kingdom]]'s human problem.<ref>{{cite book|author=Anders, Lt.-General W\u0142adys\u0142aw|title= An Army in Exile|publisher= MacMillan & Co. Ltd|date=1949|page=73}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Polish Underground Army, the Western Allies, and the Failure of Strategic Unity in World War II|author=Peszke, Michael Alfred|publisher=McFarland|date= 2015|isbn=978-1-4766-10276|page=70}}</ref> This trade-off adumbrated the [[Tehran Conference|Tehran]] and [[Yalta Conference]]s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Identity in Flux. The Polish Community in Britain|author=Sword, Keith|place=London|publisher=School of Slavonic and East European Studies - SSEES Occasional Papers No. 36| date=1996|isbn=0-903425-60-2|pages=24\u201330|url=https://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/id/eprint/10078280/1/SSEES0012.pdf|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Brushes with death==\nRetinger narrowly avoided perishing in the sea off [[Gibraltar]] with [[Wladyslaw Sikorski's death controversy|W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]], in July 1943, but for the fact that he was not needed to accompany the premier on a troop inspection in the Middle East and would be better employed in London. The spare seat on the plane went to Sikorski's daughter who died with her father.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> Retinger was devastated by this turn of events. His relationship with Sikorski's successor, [[Stanislaw Mikolajczyk]] was much more ambivalent, but he obtained his consent for a special mission to Poland under [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]] in April 1944.<ref>Bu\u0142hak, W\u0142adys\u0142aw. \"The Foreign Office and the [[Special Operations Executive]] and the Expedition of J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger to Poland, April\u2013July 1944\", ''[[The Polish Review]]'', vol. 61, no. 3, 2016, pp. 33\u201357.</ref>\n\nWith an SOE brief and without prior training, Retinger, aged 56, parachuted into [[German-occupied Poland|occupied Poland]] with 2nd Lt. [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt]], (see [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt#Operation \"Salamander\"|Operation Salamander]]), to meet with Polish underground figures, to deliver money to the Polish underground, and to \"explain to his fellow Poles in the homeland 'how are we going to lose this war'\".<ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\">{{cite book|last1=Eringer|first1=Robert|author-link=Robert Eringer|title=The Global Manipulators|publisher=Pentacle Books|asin=B00546KTEM|oclc=26551991}}</ref>{{rp|pages=16\u201322}} <ref name = \"JR\"/>{{rp|page=265}}<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>  Following at least one assassination attempt on him, Retinger expressed his frustration thus:\n\n{{blockquote|You know why I came.  The [Underground] [[Government Delegation for Poland|Delegate]] knows as well.... They know that I only want to convince them that it will be necessary in the future to cooperate with the Communists, because no English are coming here, only Russians.  If we do not get along with them somehow, it will be a terrible tragedy, because we well know what [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]] and the [[NKVD]] [Interior Ministry of the Soviet Union] are.  And it's about trying to make people here understand this fact.  And they want to murder me!<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>\n\nThe latter quip was a reference to elements in the [[Polish Underground Army]], the [[Armia Krajowa|AK]] who were convinced Retinger was not serving the interests of his country and should therefore be \"removed\". One apparent attempt to liquidate him in Poland was on the grounds of a \"death sentence\" to be carried out on the alleged orders of general [[Kazimierz Sosnkowski]]. It was foiled by the intervention of an old friend and [[Armia Krajowa|AK fighter]], Tadeusz Gebethner.<ref>{{cite web|title=The story of Tadeusz Gebethner|url=https://sprawiedliwi.org.pl/en/stories-of-rescue/story-tadeusz-gebethner|publisher=sprawiedliwi.org.pl |access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> There was also an attempt during his visit in occupied Poland to poison him, which failed. On his return to London, he spent some time in the [[Dorchester Hotel]] in London's [[Park Lane, London|Park Lane]] recovering from his ordeal of the trip, which left him lame in one leg for the rest of his life, possibly due to the [[Polyneuritis]] brought on by the poison. His first visitor at the Dorchester was Sir [[Anthony Eden]], the foreign secretary.<ref name=\"Davies\"/><ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\"/>\n\n==Vision for Europe==\n[[File:Krakow-Jozef Retinger plaque.jpg|thumb|right|[[Krak\u00f3w]] plaque commemorating Retinger, \"great pioneer of European unity\".]]\nAfter World War II, Retinger feared another devastating war in Europe, this time fought between \"Russia\" and \"the Anglo-Saxons\".<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/> He became a leading advocate of [[European unification]] as a means of securing peace.<ref>{{cite web|author=Retinger, J. H.|title= The European Continent? Address given to the Royal Institute of Foreign Affairs in London|url=https://www.cvce.eu/content/publication/2008/2/19/534c684a-8924-445a-8181-58360f939f56/publishable_en.pdf|publisher=CVCE|date= 7 May 1946|access-date=2020-03-27}} Correction: although the original states Royal Institute of Foreign Affairs, it should read [[Royal Institute of International Affairs]], known today as \"[[Chatham House]]\", this is likely a copyediting error at CVCE (ed.).</ref> He helped found both the [[European Movement]] and the [[Council of Europe]], somewhat to the dismay of the philosopher Count [[Richard Coudenhove-Kalergi]], the post-[[World War I]] [[Anti-communism|anti-bolshevist]] founder of the [[Paneuropean Union]] movement.<ref>{{cite book|title=The CIA, the British Left and the Cold War: Calling the Tune? Studies in Intelligence|author= Wilford, Hugh|publisher=Routledge|date= 2013|pages=227\u2013228|isbn=978-1135294779}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1|page=165}}</ref> \n\nRetinger, with his connections in Holland, Belgium, and [[Switzerland]] (he was a friend of [[Denis de Rougemont]]), took his cue from [[Winston Churchill]]'s 1947 [[Zurich]] speech and found fertile ground with thirteen British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] members of Parliament who backed the idea of a loose European association of states. Working in particular with Britain's [[Duncan Sandys]], incidentally Churchill's son-in-law, he took on the lion's share of the work and became Honorary Secretary General of the [[European Movement]]. He organised the 1948 [[Congress of Europe|Hague Congress]] which brought together the two camps of those for a unified Europe and those in favour of a federal Europe.<ref name=\"Lane\"/> During the congress, Retinger networked assiduously among the delegates, who included the Vatican diplomat, [[Giovanni Montini]], the future [[Pope Paul VI]]. Ensuing discussions led eventually to the formation in 1951 of a [[European Coal and Steel Community]].<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>  \n \nRetinger initiated the informal [[Bilderberg Group|Bilderberg]] conferences in 1954 and was their secretary until his premature death in London. Despite eschewing any distinctions or medals throughout his life, in 1958 he was nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.nobelprize.org/nomination/archive/show.php?id=15660 |title =Nomination for Nobel Peace Prize: Joseph Retinger |author =Nobelprize.org |publisher =Nobel Media AB 2014 |website = Nomination Database| date = |access-date = 2014-10-09}}</ref> He died in poverty of lung cancer.<ref name =\"BP\">{{cite web|title=J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|url=https://kangur.uek.krakow.pl//biblioteka/retinger/B.%20Podgorski%20-%20J.H.%20Retinger%201888-1960.pdf|lang=pl|page=53|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> He was buried at [[North Sheen Cemetery]] in the presence of five British cabinet ministers as well as of his two younger daughters who were finally reconciled with him.<ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\"/>{{rp|pages=16\u201322}} According to the oration of Sir [[Edward Beddington-Behrens]], Retinger not only had special access to [[10 Downing Street]] but also to the [[White House]].<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> \n[[File:Gr\u00f3b J\u00f3zefa Hieronima Retingera.jpg|thumb|right|Retinger's grave, [[North Sheen Cemetery]], London]]\nRetinger's long time personal assistant and the editor of his posthumous memoirs, John Pomian, actually {{Interlanguage link|Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz|pl}}, was another Polish emigr\u00e9 in London, later a director of the Heim gallery in London's [[St James's]], owned by the influential Polish art historian and philanthropist, [[Andrzej Ciechanowiecki]].<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://nekrologi.wyborcza.pl/0,11,,373783,Jan-Pomiana-B%C5%82awdziewicza-kondolencje.html | title =Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz | trans-title=Obituary of Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz|journal = nekrologi.wyborcza.pl |date=2015| lang = pl | access-date = 2016-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRetinger married twice. In 1912 he wed the well-born Otolia Zubrzycka (divorced 1921, died 1984), with whom he had a daughter, Malina. In 1926 he wed Stella Morel (died 1933), daughter of French-born pacifist and [[Dundee]] member of Parliament [[E.D. Morel]] and Mary, n\u00e9e Richardson, with whom he had two daughters, Maria and Stasia. \n\nDuring his interwar travels, Retinger fell under the spell of several women, especially the American journalist [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]], a lover of Joseph Conrad.<ref name= \"JM\">{{cite book|title=Joseph Conrad: A Biography|author= Meyers, Jeffrey|\npublisher=Rowman & Littlefield|date= 2001|page=361|isbn=978-0-8154-11123}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Athens Observer|first=Donald E.|last=Wilkes|title=Jane Anderson: The Nazi Georgia Peach|url=http://digitalcommons.law.uga.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1019&context=fac_pm|date=May 18, 1995|page=5|accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref> Retinger's own liaison with Anderson brought about the breakdown of Retinger's marriage to Otolia and drove a wedge between him and his friend Conrad.<ref name= \"JM\"/>{{rp|page=293}}\n\n==Controversy==\nOver sixty years after his death, the left-leaning Retinger continues to attract fascination and controversy with, on one hand, admirers of his political skill, his apparently selfless single-mindedness and his lasting institutional legacy in Europe and beyond.<ref>{{cite book|author=Wisnewski, Gerhard|title=The Bilderbergers Puppet-Masters of Power?: An Investigation into Claims of Conspiracy at the Heart of Politics, Business and the Media|translator=J. Collis|trans-title=Drahtzieher der Macht (2010)|date=2014|place=West Sussex|publisher=Clairview Books|isbn=978 1 90557075 1|pages=63-66}}</ref> On the other hand, detractors impugn his influence due to alleged connections with deeply secret and malign factions for which there is so far no reliable evidence.<ref>{{cite journal|author=K\u0119der, Wojciech|title=Recenzje: Bogdan Podg\u00f3rski, J\u00f3zef Retinger prywatny polityk, Universitas, Krak\u00f3w 2013, ss. 417.\n|journal=Studia Sandomierskie 23|date= 2016|pages=303-314|lang=pl|trans-title=Review of Bogdan Podg\u00f3rski, ''J\u00f3zef Retinger private politician''. Krak\u00f3w: Universitas. 2013, pages 417.|url=https://journals.indexcopernicus.com/api/file/viewByFileId/84684.pdf}}\n</ref> He remains an enigma and probably the one significant contributor to post-war European peace without a monument.<ref name = \"BP\"/>{{rp|page=60}} \n\nIn 2000 [[The Daily Telegraph]]'s [[Ambrose Evans-Pritchard]] revealed from declassified US Government records that:\n{{blockquote|The leaders of the European Movement \u2013 Retinger, the visionary [[Robert Schuman]] and the former Belgian prime minister [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] \u2013 were all treated as hired hands by their American sponsors. The US role was handled as a covert operation. ACUE\u2019s funding came from the [[Ford Foundation|Ford]] and [[Rockefeller Foundation]]s as well as business groups with close ties to the US government.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/1356047/Euro-federalists-financed-by-US-spy-chiefs.html|title=Euro-federalists financed by US Spy Chief|author= Ambrose Evans-Pritchard|date=18 September 2000|publisher= The Daily Telegraph|author-link=Ambrose Evans-Pritchard}}</ref>}} The finding, in the context of the [[Cold War]], was subsequently analysed in greater detail by ''[[Le Figaro Magazine|Le Figaro]]'' commentator, {{Interlanguage link|R\u00e9mi Kauffer|fr}} in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kauffer, R\u00e9mi|title=Quand la CIA finan\u00e7ait la construction europ\u00e9enne - Par R\u00e9mi Kauffer, Source : Historia 2003|date=12 June 2019|url=http://www.comite-valmy.org/spip.php?article516|publisher=Comit\u00e9 Valmy|lang=fr|trans-title=When the CIA financed the construction of Europe by R\u00e9mi Kauffer, source: Historia 2003|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> However, as Hugh Wilford demonstrates, the initiative to win American backing for a \"United States of Europe\" did not come either from [[Allen Dulles]], deputy, then chief of the [[CIA]], nor from Senator [[William Fulbright]], chairman of the [[ACUE]], but from the lobbying Europeans themselves guided by disparate motives, namely Coudenhove-Kalergi and Retinger who eclipsed him due to his close connection with [[Winston Churchill]] on European matters.<ref name=\"wilford\"/>\n\n== Selected works==\nBy J. H. Retinger:\n* {{cite book|date= 1908|title=Le conte fantastique dans le romantisme fran\u00e7ais|place= Gen\u00e8ve|publisher= Slatkine Reprints, 1973|trans-title=Fantastic Tales in the French Romantic Tradition}}\n* {{cite book|title=Histoire de la litt\u00e9rature fran\u00e7aise du romantisme \u00e0 nos jours|place= Paris|publisher=[[Bernard Grasset| B. Grasset]]|date= 1911|trans-title=The History of French Literature from Romanticism to the Present Day}}\n* {{cite book|title= The Poles and Prussia|place=London|date=1913|url=https://explore.library.leeds.ac.uk/special-collections-explore/334918/the_poles_and_prussia?subject=%22Polish%20question%22&resultOffset=2}} available at University of Leeds Library\n* {{cite book|title=La Pologne et l'\u00c9quilibre europ\u00e9en|place= Paris|date= 1916|trans-title=Poland and the Stability of Europe}}\n* {{cite book|title=Morones of Mexico; a history of the labour movement in that country|place=London|publisher= The Labour Pub. Co. Ltd.|date= 1926}}\n* {{cite book|title=Tierra mexicana; the history of land and agriculture in ancient and modern Mexico|place= London|publisher= N. Douglas|date= 1928}}\n* {{cite book|title=Polacy w cywilizacjach zagranicznych|trans-title= Poles in Foreign Civilizations|place=Warsaw|date= 1934}}\n* {{cite journal|title= Historja i polityka: Nowy czynnik w dyplomacji mi\u0119dzynarodowej|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie (50)|date= 4 December 1938|trans-title=History and Politics: A new factor in international diplomacy}}\n* {{cite journal|title= Historja i polityka: Zast\u00f3j w mi\u0119dzynarodowej dzia\u0142alno\u015bci Rosji|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie (51)|date= 11 December 1938|trans-title=History and Politics: Suspension of Russian activity in international relations}} \n* {{cite book|title=All about Poland: facts, figures, documents|place= London|publisher= Minerva Pub. Co.|date= 1941}}\n* {{cite book|title=Conrad and His Contemporaries |year=1942 |publisher=Roy |publication-place=New York|orig-year=First published by Minerva, London, 1941}}\n*  {{cite book|title= The European Continent? Address given to the Royal Institute of International Affairs in London|url=https://www.cvce.eu/content/publication/2008/2/19/534c684a-8924-445a-8181-58360f939f56/publishable_en.pdf|date= 7 May 1946|place=London}}\n*  {{cite book|title=The Bilderberg Group|place= Hertfordshire, UK|date= 1959}}\n*  {{cite book|title=Under Polish eyes|place=United Kingdom|publisher= Joseph Conrad Society|date= 1975}}\n\nAbout Retinger:\n* {{cite journal|author=Poraj, Stanis\u0142aw|title= \"The knight among nations\"|journal= Tydzie\u0144 Literacki Polski Zbrojnej, 2 (24)|lang=pl|date= 19 June 1938}}\n* {{cite book|author=[[Denis de Rougemont|de Rougemont, Denis]]|date= 1961|title=A Biographical Sketch. In Tribute to a Great European|editor= Retinger, J.H.|pages=20\u201350|place= Geneva|publisher= Centre Europe\u00e9ne de la Culture|lang=}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Siemaszko, Zbigniew Sebastian|date=1967|title= Retinger w Polsce 1944 r.|place=Paris|journal= Zeszyty Historyczne, 12|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|title=J\u00f3zef Retinger: Memoirs of an Eminence Grise|editor=Pomian, John|publisher= Sussex University Press/Chatto & Windus|date= 1972| isbn=0-85621-002-1|oclc=844436367}}.\n* {{cite book|author=[[Jan Nowak-Jeziora\u0144ski|Nowak, Jan]]|title= Kurier z Warszawy|place= London|publisher= Odnowa|date= 1978|lang=pl|isbn= 0-903705-37-0}}\n* {{cite book|publisher=[[Polski S\u0142ownik Biograficzny]]|title= J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|volume= XXXI|date= 1988-1989|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|title=In remembrance of Joseph Retinger 1988-1960, Initiator of the European League for Economic Cooperation|publisher= [[European League for Economic Cooperation]]|place= Brussels|date= 1996}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Grosbois, Thierry|date= 1999|title=L\u2019action de J\u00f3zef Retinger en faveur de l\u2019id\u00e9e europ\u00e9enne 1940-46|journal= [[European Review of History]] \u2013 Revue europ\u00e9enne d\u2019Historie| volume= 6 (34)|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Kalicki, W\u0142odzimierz|date=2010|title=Gracz, kt\u00f3ry budowa\u0142 Europ\u0119|trans-title=The Player who built Europe|journal= [[Gazeta Wyborcza]] no. 219|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|title= J\u00f3zef Retinger \u2013 prywatny polityk|trans-title=J\u00f3zef Retinger - a private politician|publisher= Universitas|date= 2013|isbn=97883-242-2351-0}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of governments in exile during World War II]]\n*[[European Movement]]\n*[[European Union]]\n*[[List of Poles#Diplomats|List of Poles]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=Bines, Jeffrey|title=Poland's S.O.E: A British Perspective: the Story of the Polish Country Section of the Special Operations Executive 1940-1946 Including the British Military Mission Number Four to Poland 1939|publisher=Polish Underground Movement Study Trust|date= 2018|place=London|isbn=978-0-9928-03056}} \n* {{cite journal|author= Biskupski, M.B.|title=Spy, Patriot or Internationalist? The Early Career of J\u00f3zef Retinger, Polish Patriarch of European Union|journal=[[The Polish Review]]| volume= 43, no. 1|date= 1998| pages= 23-67}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Bu\u0142hak, W\u0142adys\u0142aw|title=The Foreign Office and the [[Special Operations Executive]] and the Expedition of J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger to Poland, April\u2013July 1944|journal=The Polish Review| volume= 61, no. 3|date= 2016| pages= 33\u201357}}\n* {{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=J\u00f3zef H. Retinger \u2013 pomys\u0142odawca i wsp\u00f3\u0142tw\u00f3rca Grupy Bilderbergu|trans-title=Joseph Retinger:  Visionary Co-founder of the [[Bilderberg Group]]|lang=pl|journal= Studia polityczne|publisher= ISP PAN|volume= 10|date= 2000}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Dzia\u0142alno\u015b\u0107 J.H. Retingera na rzecz zjednoczonej Europy|trans-title=Joseph Retinger\u2019s Work for a United Europe|journal= Studia Europejskie|publisher= Centrum Europejskie Uniwersytetu Warszawskiego|volume=  16|date= 2000|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Dzia\u0142alno\u015b\u0107 J\u00f3zefa Hieronima Retingera na rzecz integracji europejskiej|lang=pl|trans-title= Joseph Retinger\u2019s Work for European Integration|publisher= Wydawnictwo Adam Marsza\u0142ek|place= Toru\u0144|date= 2008|isbn=978-83-7611-184-1}}\n* {{cite book|author= Hampson, Robert|title=Conrad's Secrets|publisher=\tPalgrave Macmillan|date= 2012|isbn=978-0-2305-0783-8}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Joseph Retinger's Vision of [a] United Europe After World War II:  Central and Eastern European Question|journal= [[The Polish Review]]| volume= 60, no 4|date= 2015 |pages= 49-66}}\n* {{cite book|author=Wisnewski, Gerhard|title=The Bilderbergers Puppet-Masters of Power?: An Investigation into Claims of Conspiracy at the Heart of Politics, Business and the Media|translator=J. Collis|trans-title=Drahtzieher der Macht (2010)|date=2014|place=West Sussex|publisher=Clairview Books|isbn=978 1 90557075 1|pages=63-66}}\n* {{cite book|title=Informal Alliance: The Bilderberg Group and Transatlantic Relations during the Cold War, 1952-1968|series=  \nRoutledge Studies in Modern History|author=Gijswijt, Thomas W.|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date= 2018|isbn=978-1-3511-8102-0}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161027232624/http://home.teleport.com/~flyheart/retinger.htm Biography of Jozef Retinger]\n*[https://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/205254911 The Polish Soviet Relations During The Second World War, photographs held by the [[Imperial War Museum]] including of Dr. J\u00f3zef Retinger on 30.07.1941]\n*[http://www.bilderberg.org/bildhist.htm#Memoirs Chapter 4, European Unity.] from ''Memoirs of An Eminence Grise'' by John Pomian,\n*[http://bilderbergmeetings.co.uk/jozef-retinger/ Bilderberg website on Retinger's life in brief]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Retinger, Jozef}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Poland to Russia]]\n[[Category:Council of Europe]]\n[[Category:Members of the Steering Committee of the Bilderberg Group]]\n[[Category:Polish politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Freemasons]]\n[[Category:European integration pioneers]]\n[[Category:Geopoliticians]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Polish diplomats]]\n[[Category:Polish spies]]\n[[Category:Secret Intelligence Service personnel]]\n[[Category:Special Operations Executive personnel]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish writers]]\n[[Category:Exophonic writers]]\n[[Category:Polish essayists]]\n[[Category:Male essayists]]\n[[Category:Polish political writers]]\n[[Category:Polish people of World War II]]\n[[Category:People of World War II]]\n[[Category:History of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Rusyn descent]]\n", "name_user": "Po Mieczu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBrushes with death", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C3%B3zef_Retinger"}
{"title_page": "Imperial College Union", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{more citations needed|date=June 2013}}\n{{short description|Student's union of Imperial College London}}\n{{Infobox Students Union |\nname               = Imperial College Union |\nimage              = [[Image:Imperialcollegeunion.png|200px|Imperial College Union logo]]|\nmotto              = |\nestablished        = {{start date and age|1907}} |\ninstitution        = [[Imperial College London]] |\nsabbs = Abhijay Sood (President)<br />\nFifi Henry (DP Finance and Services)<br />\nThomas Fernandez-Debets (DP Clubs and Societies)<br />\nAshley Brooks (DP Education)<br />\nShervin Sabeghi (DP Welfare) <ref>[https://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/]</ref> |\nlocation           = [[South Kensington]]<br>[[London]], {{postcode|SW|7}} |\nmembers            = {{circa}} 17,000 total |\n\nfree               = |\nhomepage           = [http://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/ www.imperialcollegeunion.org] |\n}}\n'''Imperial College Union''' is the [[Students' Union|students' union]] of [[Imperial College London]]. It is host to many and varied societies, and has student bars situated around [[Albertopolis]]. The Union is based in the north wing of the [[Beit Quadrangle]] on [[Prince Consort Road]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Union Building, Beit Quadrangle from Kensington Gore.jpg|thumb|Union Building from Kensington Gore]]\nThe establishment of a students' union was recognised with the construction of the north building of Beit Quad in 1910-11 designed by [[Sir Aston Webb]]. The original idea for the building came from [[Arthur Dyke Acland|Sir Arthur Acland]], a member of the governing body, who saw the need for a place for students to congregate and develop a collegiate social life.<ref>[http://www.imperial.ac.uk/centenary/timeline/1910.shtml]</ref>\n\n=== Timeline ===\n{{prose|date=September 2013}}\n* 1907 Formation of Imperial College of Science and Technology incorporating the [[Royal School of Mines]], the [[Royal College of Science]] and [[City and Guilds College]]\n* 1907 Imperial College Union formed as a federation of the 3 College Unions\n* 1911 The Union building in South Kensington is constructed\n* 1922 Founder member of NUS (leaves for the first time in 1923)\n* 1949 [[Felix (newspaper)]] is founded\n* 1969 First directly elected sabbatical President <ref>See [[Felix (newspaper)|Felix]] issues of {{cite web|url=http://felixonline.co.uk/archive/IC_1969/1969_0274_A.pdf|title = 6 March 1969}}and {{cite web|url=http://felixonline.co.uk/archive/IC_1969/1969_0275_A.pdf|title = 20 March 1969}}</ref>\n* 1984 The Union starts catering operation\n* 1985 The Union Starts running own bars\n* 1987 First professional welfare advisor at the Union\n* 1988 Imperial College School of Medicine is established at St. Mary\u2019s\n* 1996 Union Council is made the supreme governing body\n* 1997 Union stops running bookshop on campus.\n* 1997 First medical student to be elected President (Andrew Heeps)<ref>{{cite web|title=Andy Heeps|url=https://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/your-union/how-were-run/committees/trustee-profiles/andy-heeps|publisher=imperialcollegeunion.org|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n* 1998 First Deputy President (Education & Welfare) Sabbatical\n* 1998 Imperial College School of Medicine merges with Charing Cross and Royal Postgraduate Medical schools\n* 2000 Merger with Wye College and Kennedy Institute\n* 2001 Sir Richard Sykes appointed Rector of Imperial College\n* 2003 College adopts Faculty structure in place of constituent Colleges.\n* 2004 College rebrands as \"Imperial College, London\"\n* 2005 Union Building Redevelopment - Project starts\n* 2005 First Deputy President(Graduate Students) at the Union.\n* 2006 Union Building Redevelopment - Construction work starts\n* 2007 Imperial College Centenary\n* 2007 The Union rejoins the NUS (again)\n* 2007 Imperial College leaves the University of London\n* 2008 The Union leaves the NUS\n* 2009 First Deputy President (Education) and Deputy President (Welfare)\n\n=== Relationship with the NUS ===\nImperial College Union is most noted for the history of its relationship with the [[National Union of Students (United Kingdom)|National Union of Students]] (NUS){{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}. Despite being involved in the founding of the NUS in 1922, Imperial College Union withdrew its membership of the NUS a year later{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}}. Since then, Imperial College Union has spent long periods outside the NUS, interspersed with brief periods of membership. A referendum for NUS affiliation held in 2002 was overwhelmingly rejected by members of the Imperial College Union.\n\nIn November 2006, after a petition proposed a debate to affiliate with NUS at [[Orientation week|Freshers' Fair]] 2006 collected 617 valid signatures, from just above the 5% minimum of Imperial College Union members necessary to call a referendum [http://live.cgcu.net/news/1290], a referendum was held between Tuesday 14th and Thursday 16 November 2006. The result of this referendum, which had a record turnout of over 30%, was a yes to NUS affiliation by 53.26% for to 46.74% against.\n\nAfter the failure of governance reform measures supported by Imperial College Union at the NUS conference in 2008, the union council voted in favour of holding a referendum on disaffiliation from the NUS.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://live.cgcu.net/news/1769 |title=Live! - Council Calls NUS Referendum<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=31 May 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608213148/http://live.cgcu.net/news/1769 |archive-date=8 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The resulting referendum showed that the Members of Imperial College Union decided that their Union should no longer affiliate to the National Union of Students.\n\n== Organisation ==\nThe Union is controlled by a variety of democratically elected representatives who sit on Union committees, control Union resources and represent the views of students to the College and external bodies. The Union is led by officers who act as representatives to the 14,900 Union members. The most senior officers are the five [[sabbatical]] officers who work full-time for the Union on a variety of areas ranging from commercial services to campaigns and representation. These officers are supported by 35 full-time and up to 250 part-time staff, and the 2,600 elected officers of the Union's 320+ clubs and societies.\n\nIn 2013, the Union successfully registered as a charity.\n\n===Constituent Union Structure===\nThere are six [[Faculty (university)|constituent]] unions which run as constituent parts of the Union. These are largely historical in origin and retain many traditions, such as their names when most of the actual faculties now have different names. Some represent the students in their respective faculties: the [[City and Guilds College Union]] (for engineers), the [[Royal College of Science Union]] (for scientists) and the [[Imperial College School of Medicine Students' Union]] (for medical students). They are all run by part-time officers elected from the student body, with the exception of the Medical Union President, who is an elected full-time sabbatical officer with a one-year tenure.\n\nIn 2002 the [[Royal School of Mines#RSM Student.27s Union|Royal School of Mines Union]] was absorbed into the [[City and Guilds College Union]] and became a clubs & societies committee. However, in 2012 after running autonomously from City and Guilds Union for many years, The Royal School of Mines regained its constituent union status, solely looking after the social aspects of its students.\n\nIn the same governance review of 2012, Silwood Park Students' Union and the Graduate Students' Association (representing all postgraduate students) also became a constituent union. The Silwood Park Union operates largely independently from the overall Union but has no part or full-time sabbatical leadership.\n\n== Clubs, volunteering projects and societies ==\nImperial College Union has a large number of student-led clubs, volunteering projects and societies (known as CSPs), with over 400 in total. Funding for CSPs at Imperial College Union is significant, taking up a sizeable portion of the Union's annual subvention provided by [[Imperial College London]], though many clubs supplement this with sponsorship from outside of the Union.\n\nCSPs at Imperial College Union are administered by the [https://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/your-union/how-were-run/committees/18-19/Clubs%2C_Societies_%26_Projects_Board Clubs, Societies' and Project Board], who deal with the majority of procedural issues and who are responsible for representing the clubs within their care to Imperial College Union. Clubs are then grouped and fall under smaller organisational boards (e.g. the Athletics Clubs Committee handles the sports clubs).\n\nExamples of notable student groups are [[InterVol|Project Nepal]] which sends Imperial College students to work on educational development in rural Nepal<ref>[http://felixonline.co.uk/archive/IC_2011/2011_1504_A.pdf Felix Online Archive, November 30 2011] Article on new Project Nepal group at Imperial College and partnership with InterVol. Retrieved 16 January 2012.</ref> and [[El Salvador Project|the El Salvador Project]], a construction based project in Central America.<ref>[http://www.elsalvadorproject.org.uk/2012/sponsors.html El Salvador Project Sponsors Page] El Salvador Project lists Imperial College Union as an official sponsor. Retrieved 16 January 2012.</ref> Other societies include sports-related societies, such as [[Imperial College Boat Club]] and [[Imperial College Gliding Club]]; music societies such as [https://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/activities/a-to-z/a-cappella Imperial College A Capella], under which [[The Techtonics]] won the [[International Championship of Collegiate A Cappella]] in 2016; social societies such as the Imperial College Debating Society. Each department also has its own departmental society.\n\nCSPs are supported by a number of features, including 15 minibuses which are available for clubs to hire. Imperial College also owns a mountain hut in Snowdonia, Wales, which it lets clubs use free of charge.\n\n==Facilities==\n===Bars===\n[[File:Beit_Quad.jpg|thumb|The Union Building forms the northern side of [[Beit Quadrangle|Beit Quad]]. The Union Bar, 568, and Metric are on the ground floor]]\nThe main Union bars are located on the north side of the [[Beit Quadrangle]]. There are three:\n*FiveSixEight is a bar serving food, with large screens often showing sports events or popular music channels.\n*The Union Bar is a small wood-panelled bar, and has existed in its current form since 1956.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/beit-venues/spaces/bars/the-union-bar|title=Beit Venues - The Union Bar|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The bar has a large selection of [[real ale]] and claims to boast the largest collection of pewter [[tankards]] in Europe, with many dating back to the early 20th century. Each tankard represents an officer of one of the clubs and only the current or former club officers are allowed to use their club's tankards.\n*Metric is a nightclub which opened in November 2010. During term time, Metric often plays host to DJs or to live bands performing to the backdrop of an electronic lighting wall. During the summer Metric hosts some of the Proms Extra events (part of [[The Proms]]).\n\nFiveSightEight and The Union Bar are both [[Cask Marque]] Accredited.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/news/beit-bars-receives-prestigious-cask-marque-award|title=Beit Bars Receives Prestigious Cask Marque award|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Union also runs the Reynolds Bar situated in [[Charing Cross Hospital]], largely frequented by the students of [[Imperial College School of Medicine]].  The bar was originally run by CXWSU for the [[Charing Cross and Westminster Medical School]].\n\nThe [[Silwood Park]] campus bar is operated by an external company, although students have pushed for a Union-run bar in recent years. The bar boasts [[Guinness]] and [[Stella Artois]] Cidre on tap and also has a small selection of bottled ales and ciders. Three flavors of [[crisps]] are available to feed hungry patrons. The bar television almost exclusively shows ''[[Big Bang Theory]]'', and there is a small stereo in the main room which students can hook up to their own musical collections if desired.\n\n===Theatre===\nImperial College Union has a theatre located in the [[Union Concert Hall (UCH)]] which is found on the second floor of the Main Union Building, Beit Quad. The majority of performances are put on by the student societies of Imperial College, ranging from serious drama through to Gilbert & Sullivan Marathons. The space is shared with the [[Imperial College Dramatic Society]] and Imperial Cinema and other student societies as a multipurpose space. The theatre has a fly tower with a selection of lighting and fly bars, the venue has lectriflex, DMX and sound & comms multicore installed throughout.\n\nIn the Summer of 2014 the Union Concert Hall underwent an extensive redevelopment after a grant was awarded to do so. In early 2015, the Dramatic Society installed a considerable amount of brand new cabling which will make the venue even more useful to anyone who wishes to use it.\n\n===Cinema===\nImperial College Union has a student run Cinema located in the Union Concert Hall, in [[Beit Hall]]. The Cinema is considered a club under the Arts & Entertainments Board, however provides a service to members and non-members.\n\nThe cinema is a professionally equipped cinema with a 33&nbsp;ft screen, Dolby Digital surround sound system, Kinoton (35mm) and Barco (Digital) projectors and seats up to 200. Pre-show advertisements are provided by [[Pearl & Dean]].\n\n===Redevelopment of the Union Building===\nAs of August 2006 \u00a32.2 million had been raised out of the total \u00a36 million required for the redevelopment of the Union wing of [[Beit Hall]]. All three phases of the building project were completed by 2011, including the full bar and nightclub refurbishment and moving the Union Gym to level 3 of the building.\n\n==Former ICU Presidents and Sabbatical Officers==\n\nNotable former sabbaticals include:\n* [[Piers Corbyn]], President 1969-70.\n* [[Trevor Phillips]], President 1975-77.\n* [[Christopher Fox, Baron Fox]], President 1980.\n* [[Pallab Ghosh]], Felix Editor 1983-84.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.imperialcollegeunion.org Imperial College Union Website]\n\n{{Aldwych Group}}\n{{Imperial College London}}\n\n[[Category:Imperial College London|Union]]\n[[Category:Students' unions in London]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{more citations needed|date=June 2013}}\n{{short description|Student's union of Imperial College London}}\n{{Infobox Students Union |\nname               = Imperial College Union |\nimage              = [[Image:Imperialcollegeunion.png|200px|Imperial College Union logo]]|\nmotto              = |\nestablished        = {{start date and age|1907}} |\ninstitution        = [[Imperial College London]] |\nsabbs = Abhijay Sood (President)<br />\nFifi Henry (DP Finance and Services)<br />\nThomas Fernandez-Debets (DP Clubs and Societies)<br />\nAshley Brooks (DP Education)<br />\nShervin Sabeghi (DP Welfare) <ref>[https://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/]</ref> |\nlocation           = [[South Kensington]]<br>[[London]], {{postcode|SW|7}} |\nmembers            = {{circa}} 17,000 total |\n\nfree               = |\nhomepage           = [http://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/ www.imperialcollegeunion.org] |\n}}\n'''Imperial College Union''' is the [[Students' Union|students' union]] of [[Imperial College London]]. It is host to many and varied societies, and has student bars situated around [[Albertopolis]]. The Union is based in the north wing of the [[Beit Quadrangle]] on [[Prince Consort Road]].\n\n== History ==\nThe establishment of a students' union was recognised with the construction of the north building of Beit Quad in 1910-11 designed by [[Sir Aston Webb]]. The original idea for the building came from [[Arthur Dyke Acland|Sir Arthur Acland]], a member of the governing body, who saw the need for a place for students to congregate and develop a collegiate social life.<ref>[http://www.imperial.ac.uk/centenary/timeline/1910.shtml]</ref>\n\n=== Timeline ===\n{{prose|date=September 2013}}\n* 1907 Formation of Imperial College of Science and Technology incorporating the [[Royal School of Mines]], the [[Royal College of Science]] and [[City and Guilds College]]\n* 1907 Imperial College Union formed as a federation of the 3 College Unions\n* 1911 The Union building in South Kensington is constructed\n* 1922 Founder member of NUS (leaves for the first time in 1923)\n* 1949 [[Felix (newspaper)]] is founded\n* 1969 First directly elected sabbatical President <ref>See [[Felix (newspaper)|Felix]] issues of {{cite web|url=http://felixonline.co.uk/archive/IC_1969/1969_0274_A.pdf|title = 6 March 1969}}and {{cite web|url=http://felixonline.co.uk/archive/IC_1969/1969_0275_A.pdf|title = 20 March 1969}}</ref>\n* 1984 The Union starts catering operation\n* 1985 The Union Starts running own bars\n* 1987 First professional welfare advisor at the Union\n* 1988 Imperial College School of Medicine is established at St. Mary\u2019s\n* 1996 Union Council is made the supreme governing body\n* 1997 Union stops running bookshop on campus.\n* 1997 First medical student to be elected President (Andrew Heeps)<ref>{{cite web|title=Andy Heeps|url=https://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/your-union/how-were-run/committees/trustee-profiles/andy-heeps|publisher=imperialcollegeunion.org|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n* 1998 First Deputy President (Education & Welfare) Sabbatical\n* 1998 Imperial College School of Medicine merges with Charing Cross and Royal Postgraduate Medical schools\n* 2000 Merger with Wye College and Kennedy Institute\n* 2001 Sir Richard Sykes appointed Rector of Imperial College\n* 2003 College adopts Faculty structure in place of constituent Colleges.\n* 2004 College rebrands as \"Imperial College, London\"\n* 2005 Union Building Redevelopment - Project starts\n* 2005 First Deputy President(Graduate Students) at the Union.\n* 2006 Union Building Redevelopment - Construction work starts\n* 2007 Imperial College Centenary\n* 2007 The Union rejoins the NUS (again)\n* 2007 Imperial College leaves the University of London\n* 2008 The Union leaves the NUS\n* 2009 First Deputy President (Education) and Deputy President (Welfare)\n\n=== Relationship with the NUS ===\nImperial College Union is most noted for the history of its relationship with the [[National Union of Students (United Kingdom)|National Union of Students]] (NUS){{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}. Despite being involved in the founding of the NUS in 1922, Imperial College Union withdrew its membership of the NUS a year later{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}}. Since then, Imperial College Union has spent long periods outside the NUS, interspersed with brief periods of membership. A referendum for NUS affiliation held in 2002 was overwhelmingly rejected by members of the Imperial College Union.\n\nIn November 2006, after a petition proposed a debate to affiliate with NUS at [[Orientation week|Freshers' Fair]] 2006 collected 617 valid signatures, from just above the 5% minimum of Imperial College Union members necessary to call a referendum [http://live.cgcu.net/news/1290], a referendum was held between Tuesday 14th and Thursday 16 November 2006. The result of this referendum, which had a record turnout of over 30%, was a yes to NUS affiliation by 53.26% for to 46.74% against.\n\nAfter the failure of governance reform measures supported by Imperial College Union at the NUS conference in 2008, the union council voted in favour of holding a referendum on disaffiliation from the NUS.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://live.cgcu.net/news/1769 |title=Live! - Council Calls NUS Referendum<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=31 May 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608213148/http://live.cgcu.net/news/1769 |archive-date=8 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The resulting referendum showed that the Members of Imperial College Union decided that their Union should no longer affiliate to the National Union of Students.\n\n== Organisation ==\nThe Union is controlled by a variety of democratically elected representatives who sit on Union committees, control Union resources and represent the views of students to the College and external bodies. The Union is led by officers who act as representatives to the 14,900 Union members. The most senior officers are the five [[sabbatical]] officers who work full-time for the Union on a variety of areas ranging from commercial services to campaigns and representation. These officers are supported by 35 full-time and up to 250 part-time staff, and the 2,600 elected officers of the Union's 320+ clubs and societies.\n\nIn 2013, the Union successfully registered as a charity.\n\n===Constituent Union Structure===\nThere are six [[Faculty (university)|constituent]] unions which run as constituent parts of the Union. These are largely historical in origin and retain many traditions, such as their names when most of the actual faculties now have different names. Some represent the students in their respective faculties: the [[City and Guilds College Union]] (for engineers), the [[Royal College of Science Union]] (for scientists) and the [[Imperial College School of Medicine Students' Union]] (for medical students). They are all run by part-time officers elected from the student body, with the exception of the Medical Union President, who is an elected full-time sabbatical officer with a one-year tenure.\n\nIn 2002 the [[Royal School of Mines#RSM Student.27s Union|Royal School of Mines Union]] was absorbed into the [[City and Guilds College Union]] and became a clubs & societies committee. However, in 2012 after running autonomously from City and Guilds Union for many years, The Royal School of Mines regained its constituent union status, solely looking after the social aspects of its students.\n\nIn the same governance review of 2012, Silwood Park Students' Union and the Graduate Students' Association (representing all postgraduate students) also became a constituent union. The Silwood Park Union operates largely independently from the overall Union but has no part or full-time sabbatical leadership.\n\n== Clubs, volunteering projects and societies ==\nImperial College Union has a large number of student-led clubs, volunteering projects and societies (known as CSPs), with over 400 in total. Funding for CSPs at Imperial College Union is significant, taking up a sizeable portion of the Union's annual subvention provided by [[Imperial College London]], though many clubs supplement this with sponsorship from outside of the Union.\n\nCSPs at Imperial College Union are administered by the [https://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/your-union/how-were-run/committees/18-19/Clubs%2C_Societies_%26_Projects_Board Clubs, Societies' and Project Board], who deal with the majority of procedural issues and who are responsible for representing the clubs within their care to Imperial College Union. Clubs are then grouped and fall under smaller organisational boards (e.g. the Athletics Clubs Committee handles the sports clubs).\n\nExamples of notable student groups are [[InterVol|Project Nepal]] which sends Imperial College students to work on educational development in rural Nepal<ref>[http://felixonline.co.uk/archive/IC_2011/2011_1504_A.pdf Felix Online Archive, November 30 2011] Article on new Project Nepal group at Imperial College and partnership with InterVol. Retrieved 16 January 2012.</ref> and [[El Salvador Project|the El Salvador Project]], a construction based project in Central America.<ref>[http://www.elsalvadorproject.org.uk/2012/sponsors.html El Salvador Project Sponsors Page] El Salvador Project lists Imperial College Union as an official sponsor. Retrieved 16 January 2012.</ref> Other societies include sports-related societies, such as [[Imperial College Boat Club]] and [[Imperial College Gliding Club]]; music societies such as [https://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/activities/a-to-z/a-cappella Imperial College A Capella], under which [[The Techtonics]] won the [[International Championship of Collegiate A Cappella]] in 2016; social societies such as the Imperial College Debating Society. Each department also has its own departmental society.\n\nCSPs are supported by a number of features, including 15 minibuses which are available for clubs to hire. Imperial College also owns a mountain hut in Snowdonia, Wales, which it lets clubs use free of charge.\n\n==Facilities==\n===Bars===\n[[File:Beit_Quad.jpg|thumb|The Union Building forms the northern side of [[Beit Quadrangle|Beit Quad]]. The Union Bar, 568, and Metric are on the ground floor]]\nThe main Union bars are located on the north side of the [[Beit Quadrangle]]. There are three:\n*FiveSixEight is a bar serving food, with large screens often showing sports events or popular music channels.\n*The Union Bar is a small wood-panelled bar, and has existed in its current form since 1956.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/beit-venues/spaces/bars/the-union-bar|title=Beit Venues - The Union Bar|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The bar has a large selection of [[real ale]] and claims to boast the largest collection of pewter [[tankards]] in Europe, with many dating back to the early 20th century. Each tankard represents an officer of one of the clubs and only the current or former club officers are allowed to use their club's tankards.\n*Metric is a nightclub which opened in November 2010. During term time, Metric often plays host to DJs or to live bands performing to the backdrop of an electronic lighting wall. During the summer Metric hosts some of the Proms Extra events (part of [[The Proms]]).\n\nFiveSightEight and The Union Bar are both [[Cask Marque]] Accredited.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/news/beit-bars-receives-prestigious-cask-marque-award|title=Beit Bars Receives Prestigious Cask Marque award|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Union also runs the Reynolds Bar situated in [[Charing Cross Hospital]], largely frequented by the students of [[Imperial College School of Medicine]].  The bar was originally run by CXWSU for the [[Charing Cross and Westminster Medical School]].\n\nThe [[Silwood Park]] campus bar is operated by an external company, although students have pushed for a Union-run bar in recent years. The bar boasts [[Guinness]] and [[Stella Artois]] Cidre on tap and also has a small selection of bottled ales and ciders. Three flavors of [[crisps]] are available to feed hungry patrons. The bar television almost exclusively shows ''[[Big Bang Theory]]'', and there is a small stereo in the main room which students can hook up to their own musical collections if desired.\n\n===Theatre===\nImperial College Union has a theatre located in the [[Union Concert Hall (UCH)]] which is found on the second floor of the Main Union Building, Beit Quad. The majority of performances are put on by the student societies of Imperial College, ranging from serious drama through to Gilbert & Sullivan Marathons. The space is shared with the [[Imperial College Dramatic Society]] and Imperial Cinema and other student societies as a multipurpose space. The theatre has a fly tower with a selection of lighting and fly bars, the venue has lectriflex, DMX and sound & comms multicore installed throughout.\n\nIn the Summer of 2014 the Union Concert Hall underwent an extensive redevelopment after a grant was awarded to do so. In early 2015, the Dramatic Society installed a considerable amount of brand new cabling which will make the venue even more useful to anyone who wishes to use it.\n\n===Cinema===\nImperial College Union has a student run Cinema located in the Union Concert Hall, in [[Beit Hall]]. The Cinema is considered a club under the Arts & Entertainments Board, however provides a service to members and non-members.\n\nThe cinema is a professionally equipped cinema with a 33&nbsp;ft screen, Dolby Digital surround sound system, Kinoton (35mm) and Barco (Digital) projectors and seats up to 200. Pre-show advertisements are provided by [[Pearl & Dean]].\n\n===Redevelopment of the Union Building===\nAs of August 2006 \u00a32.2 million had been raised out of the total \u00a36 million required for the redevelopment of the Union wing of [[Beit Hall]]. All three phases of the building project were completed by 2011, including the full bar and nightclub refurbishment and moving the Union Gym to level 3 of the building.\n\n==Former ICU Presidents and Sabbatical Officers==\n\nNotable former sabbaticals include:\n* [[Piers Corbyn]], President 1969-70.\n* [[Trevor Phillips]], President 1975-77.\n* [[Christopher Fox, Baron Fox]], President 1980.\n* [[Pallab Ghosh]], Felix Editor 1983-84.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.imperialcollegeunion.org Imperial College Union Website]\n\n{{Aldwych Group}}\n{{Imperial College London}}\n\n[[Category:Imperial College London|Union]]\n[[Category:Students' unions in London]]\n", "name_user": "Shadowssettle", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:+img from gore", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperial_College_Union"}
